\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid7218946 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you tell me your full name and present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Stanley Wilson Bailey, 20 South View Road, N.8.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you tell me your year of marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes - 19 - September the twenty-sixth 1917.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you tell me your year of birth and your birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 1892, September the second.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Whereabouts was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 144 High - Welborn Road, Tottenham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many years did you live in the house you were born in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh that's a bit of a - that's a bit dicey that is because those days you could change houses whenever you liked. I suppose as far as I can remember I must have lived 
in there at least - seven years. Yes. Then we went from various other houses according to what we wanted to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You moved around quite a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, quite a bit, yes, in Tottenham we moved around quite a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Always in the Tottenham area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 In the Tottenham area right up until I was married. So I knew a good bit of Tottenham and Tottenham Marshes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you remember why the family made these moves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - I suppose they got fed up with living in - you see, it was easy to move in th
ose days, if you got fed up with a district or a house or a neighbourhood you could move into another place quite simple, overnight, because - they used to do in what - what we call - used to call in those days, the midnight - fling. If you couldn't pay t
he rent, and you were - landlord was after you well you'd suddenly be - your house'd be empty and they would have to find out where you was living. In those days. It was easy from one house to another in the middle of the night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your family ever do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, we never did that because my father was - was very - brought up strictly religious, I was brought up very religious. Very religious. I mean and he would never do anything that was - morally against the law or anything else you see, and I 
was brought up that way you see. But we moved - well, one of the reasons why we did move, I can remember, my sister got married, and she lived with us for some time, 'til they got another - I suppose like it is today. She lived with her mother. So we live
d
 in Chestnut Road then, near the police station, we used to - in those days we used to - have a saying, High Cross Row, we lived in High Cross Road, that's right, we lived in High - and we used to have a saying in those days, up and down the High Cross Ro
a
d, in and out the Eagle - that was a public house at the top, that's the money - that's the way the money goes, pop goes the weasel. You see? Whether that was the original - balled of those days I don't know, but that's what we used to sing, up and down t
he High Cross Road, in and out the Eagle, that's the money goes pop goes the Weasel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 The original one's the City Road isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well it may have been City Road, but that was a - that was what we used to say in our area.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 I had - five brothers and two sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you give me birth order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - that's a bit - because - my father - my parents - had two editions of - of children. They had one that - there was a big gap between my sister and myself. And the next -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were you one of the young ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Young ones, I was a younger one. The older ones were more or less - young men by the time I was - knocking about. So I would have a job to - he come - I know he came from Hackney, my
 father was a - was a - cabinet maker in Hackney and he - we - he walked from Hackney - to - his first place in Tottenham, that was Markfield Road, Tottenham, he walked all the way. Pushed his - pushed his - furniture - what furniture be had on a barrow t
o - from Hackeny to - Bethnel Green rather. To - Markfield Road, Tottenham, which - is a - three - it's been re - re-modernised all round Markfield Road, Tottenham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many young brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh, I never - I - younger siste
r and myself. The old - all the others were elderly. I had a brother killed in the first world war, that's - there was a big gap between - well my brother who was killed in the first world war was ten years older than me, that'll give you an idea of the g
ap.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Was he the eldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, he was - he was - he was the next youngest you might say. I've got a brother ninety-three. In Colchester, where you - near where you are. I just buried a sister ninety-one. She wouldn't have died if she hadn't have - f
allen over and broke her thigh. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You're a long living family then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh yes. Father was ninety-four when he died. He poor old mum, 'cos she - women in those days, they looked old at seventy. Women in those days looked very old, they used to have the old poke }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 
ponder}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
, their old - cape and bustle and long skirts. And they all looked old - women at seventy were - looked seventy in those days. Those that - I'm talking about those who - who used to knockabout in the working class area. They looked ol
d, because they wore themselves out - you - you come to do the washing with a scrubbing brush and a - scribb}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
ing board, an old zinc bath. An old mangle which go clankety clank out the back yard. Used to turn it like that, used to go clankety clank, great b
ig weight on one end and a handle down the other, you - clankety clank, clankety clank. As the clothes went through, and the wooden rollers and a zinc bath underneath used to - used to do the washing then in those days in a wash house. An old copper.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 And you did that at home did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Always did that at home. Well some people used to take washing in to make a living. Some people - some women used to take washing in, in fact, and they used to do some lovely washing in those days. It was all scrub a
nd hard. No - no mechanical aid at all. There was a - was later on I believe there was a tub used to - with a - kind of a - what they used to call it, it was a lever, it had a - tub and you get a - half a dozen - half a dozen sticks in it, pegs at the bot
tom of a - well a kind of a round ring and a handle at the top and they used to twist it round. I - I don't - oh they got a - they had a name for it, I forget now what it was, such a long while ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your mother work before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 We
ll I wouldn't know. I wouldn't know because when I was a - when I was - come into the world - she was fetching up a family. And she had no time to go to work. 'Cos she was looking after the other kiddies so she had - never had no time to go to work. But i
f there was any work to be done it was always housework, it would have to be somebody's house. It would all be charring or washerwoman. As they used to call it, Washerwoman.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did she do any part time work like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. She never did that, she was too old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - she died when she was seventy-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What year did she die?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh - I've got it here if you like to keep -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Was your father always a cabinet maker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 He was always in cabinet making, yes. He was always a cabinet maker. And when they - when the war came }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  Turnpennies, the firm na}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 me of Turnpennies - went round B}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 ethnel Green - buying up all the little small cabinet makers who used to - do these cabinet making jobs for a living you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you ever remember your father being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, I never known him - he was never out of work. Because he was - more or less working for a family. There was - there was - there was a group - family - two brothers, sister-un-
law, and they was all - making these - small cabinets. You - articles that - didn't require much - effort but sufficient to - to earn a bob or two you see. - 'Cos I mean to say, living was - fairly cheap - in those days, I mean to say - you could go and -
 buy a - pound of butter for a shilling. Which makes a little bit of difference, a box - Bryant and Mays matches was a twelve - twelve boxes for a - for tuppence, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Newlyn Road you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, Newlyn Road in Bruce Grove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 About what age were you when you lived there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
I suppose I must have been about - ten or eleven. Stayed there quite a long time. My father moved from there to High Cross Road - because he had a caretaker's job - he was - he had a part time job as a caret
aker at a - at a mission. And the - there was a house going with this caretaker's job in the London City Mission Hall. And - my mother, and him used to be - take charge of the care - cleaning of the - mission. For a small sum, about - five shillings a wee
k or something like that, which - was - acceptable - for anybody with a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 They got a house rent free did they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well no, they had to pay rent. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 About how old were you when you made that move then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well I'd just started work. Yes, '
cos I asked - I had to ask permission - from my firm if I could - have the day off to help them move. So that's how I remember, I must have been about fifteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So we'll talk about this house at Newlyn Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Newlyn Road. Well - I was at school th
en. And I used to live next door to my - school - day school teacher who was also my - also my Sunday school teacher. And - I used to - earn - a copper or two because we used to - I suppose you'd call them ball - ball boys. Most of the - teachers - or gro
u
ps of - professional men like teachers and things like that, was - used to go in for tennis quite a lot, there was a load of tennis courts, you - don't matter what park you had - there was tennis courts everywhere, and there was private tennis courts and 
a
ll in those days. Lot of 'em. And they used to have a tennis club, then on Saturday afternoon - me being a monitor at school - and my teacher - I living next door, my teacher said, would you like to be a bellboy? Picking up all the balls wherever they wen
t you see. That was at Saturday afternoon, which - you - never you got - you never b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
t any sum of money but they used to - whip round to the - put a hat round for the ball - for the ball}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
boy. And not only that, they used - we - we used to love it, 'cos my -
 sister, younger sister - and me mother and father used to - like me to do these because they used to - sent me down the road - to buy cakes, used to have a - cup of tea, have a tea break you see, fancy cakes. Which we never hardly saw. But being a - a pr
ofessional people they had that little bit of extra - dough, which they could afford to spend, so they used to buy tea - fancy cakes, make their own tea, and any cakes over we used to - they used to share among the ball}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 boys so we used to - my sister used s
ay, got any cakes Stanley? And of course had a - here's three or-four cakes left over and of course - there was a dip in then. For us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So that would be an extra bit of luxury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes. Yes. That was what I used to do and I used to have - I - ther
e was no set sum of money you know, it was just simply a club round for the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How much would you get, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh only a few shillings. That's a long while ago, it was only a few shillings, wouldn't amount to anything much - according to
 today, but in those days even if you got a couple of bob - it was a lot of money. A lot of money you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many rooms were there in this house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well they're mostly - mostly the same as what you are now, they haven't altered much all round he
re, there used to be about - five or six rooms that they split up into two - two halves you see, there was a top half - and a bottom half, you could make - you could easily house - house two families in 'em and I - I suppose they do now really. But -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many rooms did your family have at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well my mother and father used to - I used to sleep in the back room. And my sister slept with - used to be one bedroom going into - into another bedroom, understand my meaning, there's a door, and m
y sister used to sleep in the little tiny room. I used to sleep in the front room. Me mother and father used to sleep downstairs - in the front room. My - she - me - she was living with me sister then in those days, married sister, she had a - she had the
 front back bedroom because she was the - V.I.P. in the house, see, so she - my mother gave her, the front back bedroom. Front - bedroom upstairs you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your uncle live with you as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Nobody else lived with us, all me brother you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were all your brothers and sisters living at home at this time or just the two young ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Only - no, there used to be me brother Will, he joined the Army. I can remember him joining the Army when they was at Millhill, they joined the Fusiliers. A
nd he come home, he said, I've joined the Army. My mother says, no you haven't. He says, I have. Because - if you was out of work, the first thing you did in those days was to join the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So really what you remember of your childhood ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 My 
sister and I was - was all that I remember. I remember. The other brothers and sisters, they were getting married or else - were already married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. No, she couldn't afford to pay anybody anything, she had to do it herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were your clothes new or second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
We used to have - well we used to have - my mum used to make trousers out of me father's trousers, you - you - the old man's cut downs you see, she always used to - the old man's
 cut downs, you never used - and me sister used to have - clothes made out of - me mother's - the best part of me mother's skirt after she wore it sometime and then she used to - take the best bit of the cloth out of it and make me sister a frock. But she
 
always kept us well - she always kept us - had our Sunday beet used to have a - a tallyman used to call round, I remember the old tallyman, used to pay so much a week. And we was - for Sundays we had a - a best clothes you see. But some people used to - i
f
 the old man - some people, if the old man had suit of clothes that was any good - they used to - the - the wife used to pop it into the pawn shop and say - so much - same as last week, guv'nor, and they used to give her a pound for the - or enough to pay
 the rent with that's all, I don't know how it was but - enough to pay the rent you see. So - when the - Friday come she'd have to get - make the money up and get the - suit of clothes out for the old man to go out on Sunday you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 But did you actually buy from second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 hand shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, used to go - used to go from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
hand shop, there was - there was even - there was even jumble sales in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Shoes you used to buy - plimsols was mostly what you used to 
go to school in because they was about the cheapest, you could go and get a pair of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 plimsols for about a shilling. C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
anvas - either brown canvas ones or - black ones. Plimsols we used to call 'em. And then boots you used to have - always - had - boots, no shoes in those days, it was mostly boots - and me father used to put - blakeys in 'em so they'd last along time.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were your boots always bought new?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh they was always bought new, yes, never give second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 hand ones because - even in those days you - your mother used to remember - used to know fact that if you - if your - feet wasn't}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 
 well shod you'd - you'd suffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  later on. She wouldn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So they'd make an effort to get you new shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 YES? WELL my mother was the boss. She was the boss, my m
other was, no doubt about it. She - my father used to come home and fetch his money and she never - she never had a week's wages, a clear week's wages. See, just depends how much he could sell you see, that - how much he sold you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 It must have been difficult for her to manage like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well it was, there was no fixed wages. They used to - used to get by though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would your father help in the house at all with any domestic chores?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - no, I don't think he would. I don't - I can't
 remember my - my father doing any help with the - the domestic chores unless it was shifting something and me mother - couldn't shift - herself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would he get coal in for the fires or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, he'd get coal in for the fire, that was ce
rtain on that because she used to say, come on, help with the grate. Help at the grate, and it used to get out - it was good enough for - she used to shout at him. Albert the grate. And he'd go and get the shovel of coal in you see. Used to have the old c
oal scuttle the side. Black diamonds we used to call 'em in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about cooking or washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Cooking and washing - cooking you had a big old - black dirty old grate, black grate. With a - always saucepans on, black - them -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316  i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 ron saucepans always stuck on top of the grate. And if you wanted any extra w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 rmth you used to open the - grate and hand down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have a gas stove as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. No, no, we never - we had a gas ring. Always had a gas ring - for quick boiling. No gas stove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about your father with the children when you were very small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - he was always - he - you see - when you're talking about children, I can't tell what he done with me - the other half of the family, 'cos I was only a - youngster but with us, he always looked after us, you could see there, there's me - and me -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about when you were quite a baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh well - I wouldn't know you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How much younger than you was your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 She was only two years younger than me
 that's all, I wouldn't know. But I know he used to look - carry me about all over the place you know, when he was only - wherever we went he went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh you went to bed at - early of a night time, 
there was no - nothing for you to do downstairs. You were shoved out, he was - you can be seen and not heard you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would your mother put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh your mother used to bath us and put us to bed, an old zinc bath in front of the fire and - put us to bed, oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How often would you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well we had a bath - we - whenever - whenever she thought we was dirty and wanted one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You didn't have a regular weekly bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, no, whenever she thought we wanted a bath she'
d give us one, all she had got to do was to get this bath out - of the coal cellar, that was in the coal cellar, hanging up in the coal cellar, take it out, put it in front of the fire, fill it with hot water. Give us a wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you remember what age you started going to bed on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - I suppose - I - I remember going to bed on me own - I remember one - I used to - I always sleep in the front room. The front - you see, all the rooms were occupied and you slept in the front room, although
 it was a - like this, was always a bed in it. And I used to sleep in the front room. And my - Saturday night my mother used to - have - give me a bath, wrap me up in a blanket and put me in bed and all the others'd be - sitting round enjoying themselves 
and I was laying in bed. 'Til I went to sleep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 That would be before you moved to Newlyns Court?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Yes, Newlyns Road, yes, well then I had me own bedroom then in Newlyns Road. Older then, 'cos I was getting old you see and - we was - kept apart. The
 sexes were always kept apart. Unless - unless there was - somebody come and - they used to shove us in with them see, used to sleep with me father perhaps. Or the mother. Somebody come and we had to put 'em up, they used to pinch my bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where did the family eat their meals, which room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Always the kitchen. What they call the kitchen. There was no front - no - kitchenette or anything, it was a kitchen. And there was always a - the scullery was a separate part of the building you see. Mostly outsi
de, it was a copper, old copper blinking old copper with - with a fire underneath it. Burn all the old rubbish in this copper washdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were there any occasions when you did eat in another room or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. No. No, we was all - I mean to say - we never ate in - in any special room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What time was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well the same as - time now as a rule I suppose, yes, first thing then you got up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would all the members of the family be there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. Sunday mornings all the members 
of the family, I can tell you Sunday morning was a ritual there, the Sunday morning with us. Well, we used to - Sunday mornings - we always had Sunday morning prayers. We all knelt down and said Sunday morning prayers. My father used to - do the prayers. 
S
unday morning prayers. All knelt down Sunday morning, all the lot. Well he - he - he'd say the prayers, and all sit down and - kneel down - I used to kneel with mother, me sister - me sister being the youngest she used to kneel, we both used to kneel with
 me mother, me mother used to sit in the chair and - and the others used to be kneeling down, me father was saying the prayers and then we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Who would be the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Me sister - eldest sister, she's just buried her now. Eldest sister, me brother 
will. And me brother Charlie and me brother - Percy, they was - me brother Percy, he got - he - he got a manager's job with Sammons - Sam}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 mons' - Sammons' is it \endash  Sammon}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
. and he had a - he - he was made manager and therefore had - he - he was able to have
 his own flat above the shop. Me brother Charlie was married, the eldest, he was married and he had his own little flat somewhere else, couple of rooms somewhere. So there was me sister, Alice. Me brother Will, and my grandma used to live with us, that's 
r
ight, my old granny. Yes, old granny, yes. She used to have it, she used - she was a lad she was. She used to have a - she always had a - always had a bird, canary. Not a canary, a - any sort of bird it wax, it was a - used to have - they called it linnet
s
? Linnets and - there was another bird. Goldfinch. Yes, a gold - chaffinch - chaffinch. Chaffinch, linnet - never had a canary, I think that was a bit too expensive a canary but it - you could always get goldfinches and chaffinches and linnets quite easy.
 
And she always had that and she always had - a glass of porter of a night time. Always had a glass of porter. And she put the poker - she used to make a red hot poker, and put this poker in the - in the porter, used to all froth up, she used to take it in
 bed and that was her night cap. Her glass of porter. Old granny never went to bed without her porter, glass of porter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How old were you when she died, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh I was in the war then. Sometime during the war, yes, I - I - I remember I 
had a - I definitely I knew I had a dream that night and I definitely - remember my - something happened to - apparition of my grandmother coming in - in my dream, and I wrote home to my sister, I said, anything happened to grandma? And she wrote back, ye
s, your grandma died. She said, I've go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 to to tell you, yes. That was - that's a fact, I had an appar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15086499\charrsid11078316 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
tion in my dream and I thought to myself - 'cos I was very favourite with my grandma. If there was a farthing going - she always used to - I used - here yo
u are, and she'd slip a farthing in me hand and my sister'd say, oh look - look at Stanley, look at Stanley. See? Stanley had a farthing. Oh yes. Farthing you must remember. She used to slip a farthing in me hand. Granny did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about during the week at breakfast, would your father be there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, he'd be at - he - he'd - well, no, you never got your father - you know what they used to do, they used to go out early in the morning in those days. You could go from Bruce Grove Tottenham or you could
 go from - that - Great Eastern Railway used to start in at Enfield and it finished at Liverpool Street. You could go - from - Enfield to Liverpool Street - for tuppence return providing you got there by six o'clock in the morning. And the fares rose - si
x
 - from six 'til half past six it was tuppence return. From half past six 'til seven it was three pence return. From seven o'clock to twenty past seven it was four pence return. After that you paid full fare. So people like my father used to go - he wante
d to go to - Hackney Downs or Bethnel Green, he used to go on the old - he used to go on the tuppence. Tuppeny fares, six o'clock in the morning. So he was never there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What would you have to eat normally for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - anything that would
 fill you up. Nothing fancy, you couldn't afford to have any fancy things. Anything you could - for - for dinner - for instance - in those days - the butchers used to cut off the little bits of the meat and sling 'em all together in - great big heaps and 
t
hey used to sell 'em to the poorer classes. There was no - making rolls of joint - making a joint now in rolls or putting the odd bits and pieces in the - middle of the joint real meat. The bits and pieces used to be put in a heap and the poorer people us
e
d to come round and buy - two pennorth of it. They used to do the bacon, used to do the same, if you wanted a rasher of bacon they used to cut all the - odd - all the odd sides off you know, pieces of fat and all that sort of thing that didn't look - to t
r
im the bacon up, and that used to be put separate on a - on a dish, and used to be lumps of bacon, all bits and pieces and the bacon used to seel - so much a pound, perhaps you'd have two penn'orth of bacon pieces, so your mother used to go and buy two pe
n
n'rth of bacon pieces and an onion and make a bacon and onion pudding. To fill you up. So - there was no - there was - Sunday, Sundays used to be - the best day of the lot, you'd go to the corner shop, buy two pennorth of blackcurrant jam - or two penn'or
t
h of raspberry jam. That raspberry jam was a - was a problem because - I think myself they had a special pip, that they used to put in 'em, call it raspberry jam, there's - there was plum and apple jam, that was all in - stone jars at the corner shop. The
 
corner shop or the general shop, whichever you like to call it. It had a - it sold paraffin oil, butter, milk - jam, treacle, black treacle, golden syrup, all loose, you know, used to be a jar of golden syrup. When we was kids we turned on the tap of gold
e
n syrup and before the - blooming proprietor knew it was - going on the floor. Then we used to scoot out for - you know - all them sorts of larks. But - used to get two penny - used to take a cup, and get two pennorth of jam. But - I think the same jam - 
u
sed to be the pips, it was called raspberry jam. But that was - that was charged a bit extra, but no one ever knew but - strawberry jam, used to buy that loose. But Sundays it was always something extra on Sundays. Of course the old - on Sundays there use
d
 to be the old - muffin man used to come round with a bell and a big - tray on his head with muffins and crumpets. Used to ding a bell about four o'clock Sunday afternoon you'd hear him going up the street, dinga-dingadinga-ding. And you - I say, well I w
o
uldn't know, but used to buy three or four crumpets or - muffins. And - I think the crumpets, I don't which was the biggest, the crumpets or the muffins but - they used to sell 'em, I know one was different to the other, and I believe the - I believe the 
crumpets was bigger than the muffins.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would you have a cooked breakfast in those days or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well we used to - cooked breakfast - yes, we used to have cooked breakfast. Used to have porridge. Start off with porridge, that used to - Quaker Oats 
same as - in those days there was Quaker Oats in those days. And Scots Oats. We used to have porridge. Bread and margarine, butter was only on Sundays. Margarine was - in the week. And syrup. Golden syrup. And - condensed milk. And they used to put conden
s
ed milk - used to buy tins of condensed milk. There was two kinds of milk in those days, there was condensed milk, Nestles - Nestles, and - other milk. You see, there was another kind of milk, I forget now what it was, but the best milk was Nestles milk b
u
t there was a cheaper milk. And there was a skimmed milk. And you could buy for about - tuppence you could buy a tin of skimmed milk. But - that - had all the cream taken out, it used to be on it, unfit for babies, you see, used to say unfit for babies. A
nd they used to buy this and we used to put - spread condensed milk on your bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about your midday meal, what did you call that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Midday meal - well - used to come home from school, my mother used to have - a stew. She'd go and buy bits and 
pieces and stew it up. Cut - she used to go round the - she used to send me round the greengrocers - greengrocers and get - twopennorth of pot herbs, used to call 'em pot herbs, used to contain a - perhaps a carrot, onion - anything like that you see, two
pennorth of pot herbs. Used to put 'em in the - stew, with a bit of bacon perhaps, or a bit of - salt beef. And make a stew. Put a few dumplings in this stew and used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So you had like a hot nourishing meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh you used to have a hot nourishing meal, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would you have any sort of pudding or sweet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh yes, used - she used to make - my mother was a devil, she used to - make a lovely potato cake. I've never had - my wife couldn't - could make - could not make my - potato cake like my
 mother. Potato cakes. Used to make cakes you see and - bread pudding. Oh bread pudding was a - was a - was a real - treat, my mother's bread pudding, everybody used to have a bit of my mother's bread pudding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What would you have in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Tea. Tea. Well jam - jam perhaps, you have a - you used to go round the corner shop and get - few pennorth of jam. Bread and margarine and jam, or else golden syrup Sundays we used to have a little bit extra. Always Sundays there was a tablecloth on on Su
ndays. In the weekday used to be a bit of - American cloth, which she used to wipe down quick. But Sundays there was always a table cloth, with blackcurrant jam or - strawberry jam, in the middle.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How would your father get on for his meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 He'
d take it home with him you see. Take bread and dripping with him. You could go and get a lovely bowlful of bread - you could get - get a lovely bowl of dripping from the butchers. Real dripping. And used to go up the road and get - twopennorth of Tottenh
a
m cake. You used to get a great slab of Tottenham cake, either pink or white. Used to call it Tottenham cake, well why they - and I think Tottenham cake used to be sold all over London, they called it Tottenham cake, whether it originated from Tottenham I
 wouldn't know but - Tottenham cake was well known in every part of London, you want - twopennorth of Tottenham cake was either pink or red. Pink or white.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would he have a cooked meal in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 He would have a cooked meal, yes, he'd have a cooked meal he would in the evening. Perhaps a chop or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So your mother would cook again for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 She would cook again, not me. Not for us, only your father. And we used to hang round the father so we had a - he always give us
 a titbit so we always - when our father came home we always hang round our father for the titbits and he used to - fish his knife and fork and give us a bit each you know, me and my sister. And we used to think it would be lovely when our father come hom
e, we had a little bit of titbit off of his plate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 He'd have something different from what you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh he'd have something different, father had something different, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What did you usually drink with your meals in those days? You say you mainly used to drink tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Tea or coffee. And - used to buy - bottle of ginger beer, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13333744\charrsid11078316 
like they do now, bottles of Co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 la, but they were different type of bottles in those days. Different types of bottles in those days. Ginger beer - sarsaparilla wine was always out. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13333744\charrsid11078316 Sarsaparilla}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  wine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your mother make any beer or wines?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, nothing like that, no, no. She didn't have an interest in making beer or wine. Some people used to make a lot of wine, used to have elderberry wine - I know quite a lot of people used to make wine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about jams or pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh she used to make her own jam, yes, she used to make her own jam when fruit was cheap. Plum jam. Plum - plums, damsons. Damsons used to make some with damsons was always cheap, damsons. Plum jam. Marmalade, used to make her own marmalade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Any pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Pickles, yes, she used to make her own pickles. Chutney. All the green tomatoes she used to make chutney out of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did she bottle any fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, she never used to bottle any fruit, no. No, never - she never bottled any fruit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did she make her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, she never baked her own bread either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you grow any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 We used to grown - my - whe
n my brother-in-law came to live with us, he was an old country chap and he used to grow the vegetables, used to grow all sorts of vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Which brother-in-law was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 My sister - eldest sister's this is, Eileen. He come from the country a
nd - he come and lived with us and then we had - started growing our own vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Is this while you lived in Newlyns?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, he started growing our own runner beans and all that sort of thing. Nearly always had runner beans in the garden, and p
eas. And beetroots, carrots. He started doing that, my father was no more - he was brought up in Bethnel Green, he - he didn't know nothing about - gardening in Bethnal Green, you never had no - never had no gardens in Bethnal Green.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where did your mother come from?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 She came from Australia. Yes. Bit of a history attached to that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How did that come about then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - my grandmother - grandma Wilson -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 This was the one that lived with you was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, she - she was a widow the
n but - she married and he - she - her name - when she got married her name was Eagle, their maiden name was Eagle. And my grandfather - Eagle - my great-grandfather Eagle was an organ builder, in Bethnal Green. He really was a big - in a big way. He - he
 
- he has re - he repaire St Pauls Cathedral organ, and he was a - he built the organ at the - Wesley Hall in - what they - where - where's that place up there in London there where the - where the - City Road, in City Road. There's a big hall there, Wesle
y Hall, and he built the organ there and he was well known in City Road, and he built this organ and - he was making - and my - grandma got married, and they went out to Australia as - like they emigrated you see, to Australia. And - wait a minute -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 The death of your grandfather was 1865 was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well he was still alive when that was taken. Now that photo was a - absolutely - almost - professional wasn't it. Very early and it's - look at it now, that's today. That's over a hundred years old isn't i
t? Well over a hundred years old. Look at it. Well he died, he went to the gold - they had a bit of gold rush didn't they out in Australia? Where they had - where they found this minerals a little while ago, in the same area they found - gold or something
,
 well he went there but he caught pneumonia and died. 'Course there was no cure for anything like that - and especially being out. My gran - my mother was the first white picaninny they'd seen in that area. Yes. Used to tell me tales about - how she sitti
n
g in Australia, the fruit was all the way round and the - and the blacks, you know, the natives used to call her the White Picaninny. And - then that - she died and my grandfather sent her two hundred pounds to fetch her family back to England, that's how
 
my mother - that's how - my mother came to England from Australia. He sent her the money, 'cos he was pretty well off. Where the money's gone to now I wouldn't know, but there's no money at all in the family now but he sent her two hundred pound - she cam
e with the old rings you know, the old sailing rigs, from Australia, took her about - I forget how many weeks to come from Australia to England. In those days she come over with about - my grandmother came home with about five children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Your great-grandfather sent her the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
My great-grandfather sent her the money. 'Cos he didn't want his daughter standard out in Australia. He sent her the money and fetched her home. It cost her two hundred quid. Or round about that way I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Then your mother was one of the children that came back with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
One of the children, yes, she was one of the children he fetched home back with her. Aunt Polly. Aunt Sue. Me mother, and a - and a - an Uncle, he - got drowned at Hull, he went and joined the
 - Merchant Navy and got drowned at Hull. So there was four of them she fetched home with her. Me - me Uncle who - who would have been alive - who - he came over from Australia with, he got drowned at Hull.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Going back to your garden did you also ever keep any hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh we kept - rabbits. Rabbits. That - when we used to catch rabbits - kept rabbits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were these for the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 They were for the table, yes, they was for the table. Christmastime they was killed. Fattened up for Christmas and
 that was a treat. Rabbit. For dinner, Christmas dinner. Rabbits and a bit of pork. That was a Christmas dinner, but we always had a good Christmas. My mother and father saw that my sister and I had a good Christmas. Used to save all the - all the bright 
p
ennies. Put 'em in our stockings - or our pillowcases, put a pillowcase up. Put 'em in our stocking. Oranges and apples, all the brightest, the best. Fill the stocking. And another - one of those cheap stockings that you - the - the - their knocking about
 
today. Used to put them in and of course we all had a - a lot of little bits and pieces and in that stockings which was - quite good for us in those days, and we buy something that's cost sixpence ha'penny, some clockwork toy and it cost sixpence ha'penny
.
 I remember I had a - a man on a motorbike, sixpence ha'penny. Cor, luv a duck, I was - king of the road then, I used to take it out and play on the pavement and all the kids used to come round and watch this sixpenny ha'penny - man on a motorbike going r
ound and round on a motorbike. Sixpence ha'penny, didn't last long 'cos it went bust and that was it. Your sixpence ha'penny had gone west then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have any company come round at Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, all the lot used to come round and we used 
to have a - we had a - a round table in the - used to sit in - in those days, and the round table used to fold up, used to turn over, understand my meaning? Used to turn up so you could put it against the wall. When you had your tea used to fetch it down 
a
nd look it. We always used to sit down when - my brother - used to come round, he - he - brother Charlie used to come round, me brother Well, and my father had a - a gun, he was - he was in the - CI.V.E's, and he still had his gun. You know the City Imper
i
al - Volunteers in those days. They went out to South Africa didn't they, contingents of 'em went out to South Africa. C.I.V's. And - my father had a - a black scalp - a - a - Zulu's - scalp, kind of a head you could slip over your head. You know, a wig, 
k
ind of a wig. See. Zulu you see. Zulu wig it was, an imitation zulu wig. Put - my brother used to put it on his head - black his face and get this gun and stand behind this - stand behind this table and - start firing - I used to get frightened you know. 
And my father used to say, now that's enough Will, didn't do no more, you're frightening Stanley.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You must have been quite young then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, I was only young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would birthdays be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, your birthday was, 
yes, your birthday, 'cos they always bought something on your birthday. But not like they are - no birthday cards about much then, I don't - I never remember - I never remember seeing - receiving birthday cards like I did, I don't know whether I did or no
t but I don't remember but I do know I had a cousin - lived at Walthmasto}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13333744\charrsid11078316 w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
, she was a schoolteacher - and she was a little bit - she was a spinster, and she had a - you know, I suppose she had a - a good - wage or - I don't know, you know, salary, so she wa
s able to afford to come home and send us - books. Always books. Books for us. Always come over and see my father - her Uncle. She gave him a - a few - shillings, to treat - she used to bought us - buy us a book. And my - cousin - she - always - treated u
s well Christmas time and birthdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So you were fairly lucky?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
I was fairly lucky, yes, having somebody who was a bit - in the money sort of light as we thought - as far as my father was concerned she was - a teacher. A school mistress in Waltham
stow, so - you can tell she was - she had a salary that was - an income which was above the ordinary - salary that you cold get in those days. She - she got more than a pound a week at any rate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have a birthday party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, no, no, no, no birthday parties. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about musical instruments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh well, my - my - my sister used - my sister used to play a - an organ, is it called an organ - used to pedal it, squeeze box sort of thing, you make - you make the wind and she used to play that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you play anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, I - I - I joined the band - I joined the band later on. A mission band, we was all - we all joined a band and we formed a football team. 'Cos in those days - nearly every street that was any street at all ha
d a football team. Yes, and - Tottenham Marshes and Hackney Marshes were full of football pitches. And you had you own football team playing one another of a Saturday afternoon.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 This would be when you were a young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, I was younger, yes, 
after I left - when - you know after I pay the - 'course you had to pay your own - expenses and all that sort of thing, well you could ride from here to Walthamstow for about tuppence. Those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Going back to your schooldays, did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh yes, we was always singing, oh we made music, always singing. My father was a good - my father used to have a lovely bass voice. And used to - all had to sing, my sister - my sister Edie, used to sing, my sister Alice used t
o sing. Oh Sunday evening was always singing in the old - his old - squeeze box. My father used to take us all - oh yes, he was a good - he couldn't play anything but he was - he knew music. He - he - he could transpose music. Yes. He used to transpose fo
r the - the Boys Brigade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, no, I don't think so, no. Not - only more than any party games that you get at Christmastime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about during winter evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well they used to be - used to go
 to bed in the evenings of course you - I mean to say there was only electric - was only paraffin lamps in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You say you used to have books from this cousin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have many books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, as a matter of fa
ct - I've kept one which I've - prized very very - very much. Show it to you. And it's still - a classic today. I believe any rate. My schooldays. And the - that was - always used to buy - comic Cuts. Chips. Tom Merry. Sexton Blake. Always had - we had - 
y
ou know, Tom Merry, as - I think it's - it's Billy Bunter and all them sort of lot of things you see. Chips used to be - used to be - Comic Cuts used to be - Mutt and Jeff. Mutt and Jeff. Chips - I don't know - all had their own characters and - when they
 
come out we all used to have 'em, used to pass 'em round. See, we had a fine time. Well I used to - what I used to buy them myself because I used to - buy the - my mother used to give me enough money to go down the - the - Tottenham and Weekly Herald Offi
c
e where they used to print the - weekly paper, buy so many, you got so much for a shilling, you got two or three extra, which you made your money out of, what you made you your - I used to go down Bruce Grove station and sell these - about half past - six
 
in the morning, sell these papers, get the odd money out and she - mother - what I made my mother used to give me so many coppers back, then I used to - on the Saturday afternoon used to go down the Spurs ground and sell programmes, and they used to do th
e
 same with the programme, used to give you a hat - you know, with the Spurs - Football Club on it and used - your ears kept it from falling over your blooming face, so - don't matter whether it fitted you or not, you had that that, that was your - that wa
s
 your - you know, status symbol that was and - used to go round the grounds then and sell 'em. Penny each. Used to - make me money that way, selling - programmes, Spurs programmes in the - and I used to come home and that with the - with the ballboys - mo
ney I used to as a ball boy, I used to be - used to have me own money. Give me mother some. She used to give me some back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So you were quite enterprising?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh you had to make your own money, you had to - you had to - you had to get - you had to e
arn - you had to earn your own living, there's no - there was no - if you didn't get - if you didn't earn your own living you never got no money, 'cos your mother couldn't give you - no - no good - saying you wanted pocket money today mum 'cos it's no goo
d
 - she had no pocket money. She - you had to earn it. Saturday morning used to - first thing in the morning used to go round - Saturday mornings used to go round cleaning knives. My sister used to go round cleaning doorsteps. So much doorsteps, you know, 
the hearthstone and - pail, she had her pail and - go round cleaning doorsteps, she had her own pail - and scrubbing brush. Clean door steps. I used to clean knives and - forks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have newspapers in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh used to buy - my father used to buy the - at Bruce Grove station, used to buy the - the - what was it called now - Daily Chronicle.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What about Sundays papers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Sunday, he never had no Sunday papers, he didn't believe in Sunday papers. No, but there was Sunday papers out, b
ut he didn't believe in 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have any magazines in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Magazines, no, we never had magazines, we couldn't afford magazines, unless they was given to us. OH yes, sorry, yes we did. My grandmother used to have - Horners - was it Horners Weekly? I believe it was called Horners Weekly. She had that. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were your mother and father very keen on reading or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, always reading, there was nothing much to do but read. Used to read the Christian Herald, the Christian Her
ald, yes, they used to have it - now it's coming back to me, Christian Herald used to have. Me mother used to have Horners Weekly. There was another Sunday paper they used to have, Sunday Companion. Sunday Companion, Horners Weekly, and the Christian Hera
ld. That - yes, we was - actually religious one if there was at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, we used to have to read. One another, used to have to read one another, we always read. These books, used to read - we
 used to have to read to grandma. Yes, if you go to grandma, you going to sleep? No, read to me Stanley. I used to read her - read to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would your mother and father read aloud like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, no, I used to read me grandmother. Used to read to me grandmother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you remember a funeral in the family before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh - yes, I remember a funeral, going to a funeral. It was a - a very some occasion in those days. You had the - the - headgear for the horses, plumes. The - top hats for the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Which period are you talking about now, when would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - when - one of my uncles died. I forget now, I remember going to it. I was a schoolboy, but it was a very elaborate - it was a very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  horse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 drawn vehicles you know and they had t
he - I remember sticking - it sticks - sticks out in my mind vivid, the plumes on the horses head. And they way they - the way - the - black long frock coats they used to walk beside of the - hearse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have to have a black tie or armband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh, we had - you had to have black, you had to have mourning. Black - black, something black, you always - anything black, if you never had black you had to have black armband. But it was black and - if you could afford it, the women wore very - veils, bl
a
ck, absolutely deep black. If a woman was - a widow, she wore widows weeds. You knew she was a widow 'cos she wore widows weeds. My nanny used to wore - wear widows weeds. Yes, even - even though her husband had been dead for a long time she still wore wi
dows weeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many people went to this funeral, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - they used to go - they - they had - used to have the - the hearse, and perhaps if you was - had a good bit of insurance you'd have - one coach, the others used to go - by f
oot you know, they used to go - used to go by foot, always - always went to - by - always went by transport you see, somehow or other but - you - you never - you couldn't afford to spend - a lot of money on - the - you know, the funeral }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316 cortege}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 . You used to have one - you used to have one - at least one - the hearse and one carriage.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many times a week did you eat meat in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - Sundays. Sundays, and then what was left on Mondays used to have what we called - bubble and squeak. We
 used to love bubble and sque}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 k. Then she used to make shepherds pie. Then she used to get the salt beef in th}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316 e middle of the week. With peas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  pudding. Salt beef, peas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 pudding - and a few dumplings. Then Sunday morning it was - then - Sunday used to come al
ong - Saturday, used to get her join at the butchers. Bit of serag end of mutton or something like that. Neck of mutton all that sort of thing, anything that's cheap and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So you'd have meat most days would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - not meat most days but - w
ell I suppose you would call it meat, it was what was left over sort of thing. Made up in some - meat made up in some form or other like shepherds pie - or rissoles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you ever remember your mother having less food so the family could have enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well my mother always went - went without. If she couldn't feed her children she was I know my mother went without, she never said, but I know she went without. She used to - I - I've had boots and shoes which I know full well she could never afford un
less she went without, I know she couldn't afford it 'cos my father, perhaps he - he wouldn't get no money until Friday when he used to flog his - used to make these things, they used to - flog 'em in - in Schoreditch, all round Shoreditch to the - to the
 
shopkeepers, you know, the furniture makers. All these - - he used to flog 'em there and as cheap as they possibly can to get money back again so they could buy some more - - wood and - start for the next following week. And they used to share out amongst
 
them what they - earnt. Used to get an old barrow and go up and down all the various - I suppose they had their own - customers, their own shops, they knew where who - you know, regulars where they could sell their stuff to but it was always beaten down, 
you can bet your life on it. They was always de}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
perate to sell. In Shoreditch and all round there that was the home of - Shoreditch and all round there was the home of cabinet makers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. No, you had to - mu
ms the word - you - every time you spoke you lost a mouthful, that's what my mother used to say. And my father was very strict at meals you know, you couldn't - you had to - you had to - say your - say your grace at the beginning and say your grace at the
 finish. And you had to ask to leave the table. There was no - leaving the table without permission. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 We had to - we had to have what
 was given to us. No more, that's the lot, if you had three slices of bread and butter there's no more today - no more - teatime there's three slices of bread and butter, I don't say that's what we had but it - if it was three slices that's all we got and
 we never got no more - than three slices.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
You could ask for a second helping if there's any left. If your father didn't want anymore you - you - you could have a bit more. But your father come first you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would he have extra food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
He would have extra food, my father would. But I don't say that he took it. He was given the opportunity of having that bit extra, I don't say my father would do it, I don't think my father would if he thought - we want
ed it, he would give it - but he was always given the opportunity of having it, he was the - he was given first choice. If there was any extra my father was given first choice, but I don't say he took it. My father was never - my father never hit me. No, 
m
y father never hit me. My mother used to chastise 'em. Used to send me down for a penny cane to the oil shop. For a penny cane and then give it to me when I got home. I remember my mother chasing me round the bedroom once because I was naughty, I hid unde
r
 the bed and she was raking me out. Oh yes, 'cos I done something wrong, she was very vexed. My mother was the rule, my - if I didn't - my mother used - I think most days in those times the mother was the - used to rule the roost. With the children. They 
u
sed to obey their mother, they would never dare - most children that I used to play with they would never dare - defy their mother. Never dare defy their mother. Their mother was always respected, if they did anything - there would - they'd say, what will
 
mum say, you see, they would dare - daren't do nothing, because they didn't want to - bring disrepute upon their mother. I've seen ; I've seen - children being hit by a neighbour, and my mother - and my mother and other neighbours used to come out, if any
 
hitting to be done I'll do the hitting, you tell me what's wrong. I'm the one that does the hitting of my child, you leave my child alone. If he's done wrong I'll hit him. Not you, I'll hit him. The mother used to say that, not the father. Mother used to 
g
o out after 'em. You hit my child, don't you dare do that again. Any child - any - any hitting to be done I'll do it. Tell me what he's done. And then she used to say, is any - anybody else involved in it besides my boy? No. Well then don't - don't - if y
e
s, well go and find the other person. Justice used to have to be done. My mother used to chase anybody that did wrong, we had to be - you had to be - obey my mother. And if we was in the wrong we used to get it. But nobody else used to dare lay hands on m
e, or my sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Was it fairly common for people to punish a kid in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
What - oh yes, it used to - I - I - I'll tell you what - I'll tell you what, the children used to get punished a jolly sight more - than what they do today. And the teachers used to punish you and all if you was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8586356\charrsid11078316 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
isbehaved yourself at school you used to go to the headmaster and he used to - even the teacher used to have to give you the cane, just hold your hand out. And used to whack you across the cane, or he'd put yo
u across the desk and whack - whack your backside. The teacher. If if was any extraordinary and something really naughty used to go to the headmaster. And he had the whipping of you, that was at school. The cane. They talk about spare the rod and spare th
e
 rod and - what do they call it - spoil the child, that was in those days. The teachers used to do that. I remember there was two boys in my class, brothers. Veers their name was, and - the teacher - the teacher himself got - very annoyed with this boy, h
e was a bit saucy so - he had him out and laid him across the desk and whacked his backside. The other brother picked the inkwell up and slung it at this teacher. Inkwell was coming out of the desk and at the teacher. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So the teachers didn't get it all their own way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Didn't get it all - oh no, didn't get it all their own way. Used to stick a drawing pin on a seat. So he sat down. Nobody knew here the the drawing pin come from. But - I mean to say, used to punish the whole class in 
those days, I mean to say, if he couldn't find the culprit he used to punish the whole class and you was kept in. They had the right to do it, I don't know - mother's used to come up in those days to see the headmaster but they never got very far. Never h
it you - never used to have to write - couldn't - couldn't write to your M.P. About you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What would your parents attitude be if you left some food uneaten on your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well you wouldn't have no more until you'd ate that lot. That was given to y
ou the next meal come along. You'd have to eat it up. No, you never finished that. You - and it's no good you, if you - if you wanted a piece of cake you had to - eat your bread and butter up and your crust and all before you had a piece of cake.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you just help yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Had to ask and it would be passed to you. Never asked - never - you never put your hand in front of anybody else, you used to have to ask to be passed to you. Tabl
e manners were very strict in those - table manners were very strict. Table manners, my mother and father and a lot of other people as well besides my mother and father. Used to be very strict with table manners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 With holding your knife and fork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
And all the sort of thing, how you behaved - no putting your - your knife in your mouth with anything on, it was your fork that went in your mouth. Not the knife. And you had to ask please and no I don't want it thank you. No thank you, yes please.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were you allowed to bring toys or a book to the table at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, you had to have that when you - no, you never read at the table, you never read at the table, you - you - your table was for meals, if you wanted to read you had to ask permission to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did all the family sit at the table for a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 All the family used to have to sit at the table for meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 All had the same places, yes. All the same place, was father's chair. As a matte
r of fact there was a special chair for father made in those days. What they call a carver. There was always a special - chair for father. The carver it was called.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Who served the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Mother. Yes, father used to cut the joint if it was - if - 
if - if it - there was a joint to be cut which was very very rare. A joint, I'm talking about the joint of beef such as a bit of brisket or something like that. That was high days and holidays
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Sundays. Well - used to have a bit
 of - brisket, in those days, you used to have a bit of brisket because - it was cheap and you got a lot of dripping out of it. And that dripping, you used to have dripping toast. That was a - that was a - Monday mornings breakfast, dripping toast. Bit of
 brisket used to buy, mother - in those days women used to know what - was the most - economical and the most }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid556850\charrsid11078316 nutritious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
 part of the meat. And they used to buy it. I mean to say, topside was - right out of the question, topside. Although it was - might do S
unday - may do Christmas time but - brisket of beef, something like that. Brisket. Bit of - and then they used to - then they used to have salt beef, used to put a bit of beef in salt. Used to be - salt beef, used to salt it yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How did your mother serve the meal, did she put it on the plates before she brought it in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Put it - put it on the plates before she brought it in. In some parts of the country when we used to go and see my aunt, you had the - you had the - you had the batter pudding
 and the - gravy before you had the meat. And then - the afters, you never had no afters at dinnertime, you had the afters at tea, what we used to call in London - we had - you had that - you always had the custard and - fruit - teatime, not after dinner.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you usually have your afters midday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Yes, used to have our afters. When I used to go and see me aunt at Kettering she used to say, what do you want, served London style or Kettering style?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Yes, my mother was very well liked. She was - a kind of a - people used to come to her for - problems and used to - she used to - try to solve 'em, for 'em. Oh, many a neighbour. Used to be a Jewess across the road - come to my mother. He had a rag and 
bone shop across the road, this Jewess. Jew }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid556850\charrsid11078316 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  Jew}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid556850\charrsid11078316  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
boy and Jew and Jewess. Come and speak to my father and tell him. My father was a very good - what shall I say - could - no - help the - he would help to solve your problems, would say, I wouldn't do it tha
t way if I was you, I'd do it so and so and I think you'll find that's the best way to do it. And my mother was always doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Was she an affectionate sort of person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh my mother, she wouldn't - she had - I suppose she had three - daughter-in-la
ws, and she never said a bad word about one of them. She would - you know what my mother's philosophy was? I'll tell you. I don't know whether I've got it the right way round but - to their faults a little blind, to their virtues very very kind. That was 
m
y mother's philosophy. She always drummed it into us. To - and she never heard any - she wouldn't hear anybody talk about nobody, I don't want to know. You had your - if I do - if I hear you say that I'll cut your tongue out. She was down on you like a to
n of bricks. If she heard you - talking about somebody. No, that's what she used to drum us into, to their fau}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid556850\charrsid11078316 lts a little blind to their vir}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 tues very very kind, that was my mother's philosophy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 As a child did you feel you could take your worries to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 I used to - used to take your worries to your mother, used to tell your mother, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Father, no, he - he - my father was very remote. Very - he never let us - he - he always there to guide us but he - m
y mother was the person we went to. My mother - if we was in trouble my mother was the person we went to. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 To them - we had to be polite. Very polite. Yes mother, no mother. Yes plea
se, no thank you, yes please no thank you. Anything that - departed from that - system was very looked - frowned upon and we was - told off about it. My father used to say, what are you talking about, who are you talking about. What are you talking to, do
n't talk to me like - that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh we had to behave ourselves - to our elders. Was respect to our elders, do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 n't matter whether we liked them }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 or not, we - we d
idn't know - you had to be respectful to the elders whether you took to them or whether you didn't. We had our likes as all kids all do to different people. We had our likes, but we daren't show it. And we had to be polite to anybody we saw. And we had to
 raise our hat. I did. You had to doff your cap. I had a cousin - what about this, I went to see me cousin in Whittisham in Kent. And - my cousin - with any - any - any of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 nobs in the village, he passed any of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
nobs in the village my cousin used to
 doff his hat, and my - my cousin that used to curtsey. That's a fact, I remember - I can remember it - went to stop there and I'm with my mother. She's holding my hand I'm sit - walking behind me aunt. And I saw me cousin doff -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What was your parents attitude if another child hurt you, would they tell you to hit back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
