\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. Yes, I spent - my brother-in-law, he - what - we went to - Stanstead Abbots. Stan - Stan - St Margarets - St Margarets, aroun
d about there you know - where we used to stay there and of course it was all countryside round St Margarets and - used to stay there for a week. In the fields all like round there, used to help in the - harvest. Used to see all the - oh when they was har
v
esting we used to see the harvester used to go round and in a square and then - as it drove the rabbits into the centre you'd see all the - as it got nearer and nearer the - the old farmer used to stand with his gun, and as they - as the rabbits shot out 
h
e used to fire at them. And he used to - share the - kill with his - farmhands you see. Used to all used to enjoy ourselves when they used to do - when they used to - do the harvesting as they drove round the field you know into a - into a square, when th
ey got right into the square and all the rabbits had all gone in, then there was a - scarper for all the rabbits and hares used to go out, and the old farmer used to - you know, fire at 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Who did you stay with there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 I used to stay with - my b
rother-in-law's brother, you know, no relation of mine. But - relations of my brother-in-law, they used to have a farm there. He - he used to be a farmer, he had his house. 'Cos in those days you had - farmers had their tied houses didn't they? You see, t
h
ey had their tied houses and used to have their chickens and - and that but they used to live in the produce of their - bit of a garden, 'cos it was a garden in those days was more - more like a - young field. Used to have all the - then they used to get 
all the rabbits as well, used to go out poaching. You could see them where they used to - poach the rabbits, they used to place snares for the old - rabbits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you ever used to get any of these poached rabbits in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. No. No. We used to 
birds nesting, but - I was a kid we used to go birds nesting but there was one - you - you - it was forbidden, it was taboo, you must never rob a wrens - a robins nest, where R was, you must - dare not rob a robin - robin red breasts nest. That was dead -
 that was dead unlucky, if you - or you - it was fatal to rob a - redbreast - robin redbreasts nest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Which members of the family used to go on these holidays with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - only my sister and I you see because the elder ones of course you - you
 - the older - my brothers and sister - my other sister, elder sister, and me other brothers - I wouldn't know what they did, they made - they made their own life, you see, because they were old enough and earning their own money you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would your father go hop picking with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh me father - all the family used to go hop picking down my aunts, oh yes, it was a family affair, and of course - we never used to have to take any - kitchen utensils 'cos we was going to our aunt and it was already t
here you see but - other families used to - used to have - used to lay a train on for the hop pickers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about the week in the country, would your mother or father go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, you - you - see - well they would - take - you know - my brot
her-in-law - guaranteed to look after us you know. Kettering - when I when I went to me Kettering me aunt in Kettering, of course I was a bit older then. That was after I left school went to Kettering.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What would you do with your Saturdays in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well there was no picture places or anything like that. There used to be one - there used to be one - what we called the Flea Pit. In High Road Tottenham. That used to have - lay on - various }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
s - things. Children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 s pictures. They was -
 more or less - still, you know, silent pictures. And the first half a dozen in perhaps used to get a monkey up a stick or something like that and used to come out and you - they used to come out like - more - you - you was - come out with more than you w
ent in with. Used to be scratching - used to call it the flea pit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have different clothes for Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, always had our Sunday best, oh yes, that was - that was - oh that was absolutely essential you had your Sunday best.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, I don't think - used to work, my father would never work. Do you know, my father - when I got married my - I - engaged a photographer and he was supposed to come on the - it was on a Saturday 
we got married. And he was supposed to come. And we waited for the photographer to come and nobody turned up, so I went up to see what had happened to him - and he's forgot to tell he was on a jury. He says, well I - he said, I'm very sorry but - you'll h
a
ve - he'll have to come to you tomorrow, that was Sunday. So - that was a bit of a - bit awkward, 'cos we'd already met and we was already there, to get the crowd back again, the - the wedding crowd back again, come on a Sunday was going to be a bit awkwa
r
d, but however we got - we got - we got all of us turned up. Except my father. Now the wedding reception was - in Nornsey. Clarence - in - Horndey, Turnpike Lane. I lived - and all my family lived at Tottenham. Everybody got there bar my father. And he wo
u
ldn't ride on a Sunday. He - he walked from - High - High Cross Road Tottenham, to Turnpike Lane and he got there about five minutes too late, the pictures had been taken. Just turned up. No, he wouldn't take any transport or wouldn't pay for any transpor
t, there wasn't much transport then but it was - it - it would have been sufficient for him to have got there in time. But he wouldn't pay no fares on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would he do anything on a Sunday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, wouldn't do nothing on a Sund}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 ay, only church work. Six days }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 halt the labour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Which denomination were your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well, we was non-conformists you see, non-conformists. Although - I was brought up at the Methodist church, my old granny had a pew in the Methodist church, used to pay in those 
days for a pew you see, family pew, my old granny had a family pew at - the Methodist church. But my father was non-conformist, he didn't believe in any - rituals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did he attend any particular place of worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 It was the London City Mission he 
belonged to. He belonged to the London City Mission which was very active in those days. It was amongst the poorer class you see, it was - it was working class you see. If you went into a - a Salvation Army and the mission halls in those days you didn't h
ave to dress up. If you went to church you had to be - put your best bib and tucker on. And that didn't appeal to everybody. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would your father go every Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Every Sunday, yes, wouldn't miss.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 My mother used to go with him in the evenings, after - you know, after she'd done the cooking and all that, Sunday cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would your father go more than once then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh he'd go two or three times he would, he'd go every day of the week if he could - go to church - was open.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you attend the City Mission?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh went to - I went to - I went to the Methodist Sunday school because - the London City Mission didn't have Sunday schools like the - churches did, most of the churches had Sunday schools twice 
a day on a Sunday. That was - there used to be hundreds of kids used to go to Sunday school. I don't say they all went just because to get the religious teaching because - they went there because there was something - there was the - the amusement attache
d to it or the - you know, the things -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How often did you have to go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
I used to to go twice - I used to go twice a week - twice a day. Had to go twice a day. You had prizes you see, used to have prizes for going. Same as the scho
ol, used to get prizes for school for regular attendance, I had many a prize for progress and regular attendance at Sunday - in the elementary schools where I went to after I left the church school. Went to Spurling Road Elementary school. And - o}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 h yes, you - you were - had to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
attend or you daren't let your class down, there was a regular attendance and there was a - banner for the - most - regular attendance class and that was the honour, used to march all the way round the school. The - the - the - class 
that had that highest attendance, and the regular attendance, they marched all round the school, oh yes, you was - you was the heros of that school that week at any rate. Used to change I suppose like anything else, you'd change from week to week but -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 They'd do this once every week would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Yes, do this once every week, attendance at the end of the week, who had the most number of attendances, less - you know, less absenteeism.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were there any other social activities attached to the church that you belong to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, there was not many social activities beyond the churches in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Was there anything else connected with the church, did you belong to a choir or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well we belonged to a - ah, when I got older. When
 I got older I belonged to a brass band. Oh yes, I belonged to a brass band, you all - oh you belonged to a brass band when you got older, you had to do something like that. And they had a - I say there was a lot of brass bands knocking about in those day
s. We - we had one at London City Mission in High Cross Road. And I belonged to that. Me brother did and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your father take any interests in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Politics? Huh. No. Politics was - you - politics were not - very popular in those
 days. No. There was only one - to be - if you want to be - like if I want to tell you - in my opinion it was the - Tories - that was predominant, wasn't Conservative party, it was the Tories and the Liberals. Lloyd George was coming into his own those da
ys, Lloyd George. But there was the Tories and the Liberals mostly. It wasn't until latter on that you became interested in politics. Because majority of places the Tory M.P. was - un}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 o}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 pposed, even in a place like Tottenham, which is an industrial area today
, you would never - and Hornsey always had - always unopposed and round about and - quite a number of boroughs in - London what's unopposed Tory candidates, never knew no election. My - my M.P., Howard his name was, he lived in Bruce Grove and he had his 
c
arriage and pair with his footmen, used to come out of there, and he used to tour the district. I mean to say it was - you bowed and scraped to those people in those days, the working class was - was more or less - you know, what do you want to know about
 
politics for. I was - I went in for that - I - when I got a bit older - I went into a barbers shop to have me hair cut like, I suppose used to have hair cuts in those days like they do now, and I was sitting there and I heard the barber say to one of his 
m
en there he said, who's going to - who you going to vote for? I think it was the Liberal party and just - Liberal party was just coming into their own. And he was - Howard was being - opposed by a Liberal. And that was quite a - an event. See? After all t
hese years of unopposed - seating. He - I was sitting there, he said, who are you going to vote for? He said, there's only one party you can vote for them, they've got the money. You see what I mean, that's how it was in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your father ever vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Not if I know, couldn't tell you,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you know what his views would have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
I think his would have been - would have been - with the Conservative myself. It wasn't until I got older and realized the fact that - I was interested in politics I went left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well mother - women never had the vote, there was no good her voting because - was no women's - franchise in those days. She was never interested, she couldn't - women was - more interested in the 
home, especially a working class woman, she had - all her - all a working class woman in those days was - how to make ends meet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well they used to make - I'll tell you wh
at my - my mother did and my sister used to do, make rugs - out of rags. Things like that. Used to do embroidery work. Yes, antemaccassars. My aunt - my gran used to do a lot of crocheting, knitting. Knitting, knitting antemacassars, knitting - curtains, 
you know, antemacassars. Used to knit them. Used to do a lot of knitting in those days, sewing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. She would - no, she had - working class women - never had much chance for - they was brought 
- all the time bringing up children, they had large families in those days. Large families. They went to bed at nine o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, my mother - well she used to enjoy herself with her own family. She - if she - saw her family happy she was happy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would she ever go out for a drink or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, she would never go out for a drink. She couldn't afford - there were - there were a class of people - round about where I lived who used to to and
 do - get twopenn'orth of gin and peel their potatoes on the doorstep of the pub. I remember the Oakworth Arms round where I used to live, there was - you could always often see women on the Saturday - dinnertime, of course pubs was open all day long in t
h
ose days, sitting peeling their spuds with twopenn'orth of gin at side of them. Oh yes, that was a - that was a regular sight. Then they used to keep open 'til late at night, especially on Saturday I think they used to keep open 'til twelve o'clock at nig
h
t. That's when you started - that's when the fun started. Twelve o'clock at night, used to see the - old coppers down - bloke got a bit obstreperous - the old hobbies in those days, there was more - there was a copper to every street in those days very ne
a
rly. And - if a bloke got obstropolous you know he - he wouldn't behave himself they used to frog march him to - frog march him. Have you ever seen anybody frog marched? Ay? Do you know how they do it? They used to turn you upside down one copper'd have -
 
one hand one copper have your arm and the other copper have your feet, they used to - you daren't struggle because every time you - you struggled so you was hurting yourself, or they used to frog - or if you - or the other alternatives, if you was - if yo
u
 was really - unconsciously drunk, they used to send for an ambulance, it was a - canvas stretcher on wheels, and the copper used to - get hold of you, stick you in the - lay you flat on this - stretcher and then - bolt - strap you up in this canvas strap
 and he used to push you along to copper station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you see much drunke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 ness and that sort of thing when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, yes. Specially Saturday nights. Oh yes, more so 'cos the pub used to be open, you could go and get pint for - pen
north of beer and - gin was cheap. Women used to drink gin more than anything else, gin - women used to drink gin a lot. Beer was - oh yes, beer was - I'll tell you what there used to be in pubs - and that was birds singing. Competition for birds. And - w
h
ippet racing, whippet racing on a Saturday and Sunday, used to go whippet racing, the men used to go whippet racing on - at - on Tottenham Marshes there. Whippet racing. Yes, that's proper - had rabbit and that sort of thing, these whippets, you know, the
se whippets, a sort of greyhound, you know, a smaller type of greyhound like a whippet and they used to go whippet racing. Then they used to go - pubs used to be filled u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 p with - l}{
