\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What time did your father get home from work in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well when he - well - late at - always late at night. Al
ways late at night. Workers they worked - every blooming hour of the day they could work because they had to do it, they - the - money was - there was no - there was no - nothing for hard luck in those days, if you didn't work you didn't eat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many evenings a week would he spend at home once he got in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, once he got in he - he was too tired to - too tired to move far.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would he ever go out to the pub for a drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. Never out to a pub for a drink no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did he drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No 
he didn't drink, he was a teetotaller. There was in those days - a - the temperance society was very very strong, there was all the Band of Hopes. Kidd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 es used to sign the pledge at - seven or eight, used to sign the pledge. Used to go to the Band of Hope, you never went to the Band of Hope to sign the pledge, you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316 went because it was a magic lant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
ern slide, but you signed the pledge 'cos it was a part of the ritual. So you signed the pledge, but you - we never thought about - I remember, now I remember a hym
n they used to sing or - though it may have been catechism. Those lips that touch - touch liquor shall never touch mine. I mean to say that's daft today isn't it? Those lips that touch liquor shall never touch mine. But that's the fact, it was there in th
o
se days. Sign the pledge. Kids about eight and nine signing - the pledge. And they say, those lips that touch liquor shall never touch mine. I mean to say it's fantastic today. The same as what they used to sing in the church, the catechism. God bless the
 squire and his relations, and keep up in our proper stations. That was the attitude to the peasant. The working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your father take part in any sport at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes I say - he used to go in for sport, yes. He used to go swimming I - as I sh
owed you a photograph, he used to like swimming. Every Sunday he used to take 'em all down the - down the Lee swimming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Who did he used to take?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 All that photograph, any - anybody - anybody that was in - I mean to say there was a band there and
 they used to take all the bandsmen down there used to take and all the prominent people of the church used to - mission used to go down there swimming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did he actually organise it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 He used to - you saw him there, used to take 'em down there, he was responsible for 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 This was from the mission was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Yes, that was from the mission. There was a lot of swimming clubs, a lot - it don't matter what organisation - what - if it was a mission or anything else, they had their swimming clubs
. That used to - the people used to make their own amusement, they formed clubs. Tennis clubs, swimming clubs, cycling clubs. The fasted thing on the road in those days was a racing bike. And you'd see 'em every Sunday morning and Saturday morning you'd s
e
e - dozens of racing bikes - racing clubs going out. With their - we used to call 'em - tyre smellers, used to - drop handlebars and their head right over the front wheel, we used to call 'em tyre smellers. See? Oh, you used to shout out, and your back wh
e
els going round, this sort of thing you - know. Used to - there was clubs in those days, everybody had to make their own amusements, there was no tin can - there was no - can affairs, no pictures, no television, no - radio or anything like that. You had t
o make your own sport. There was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would your father go to the races or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh he'd go to the races. He liked racing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would he have a bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, I don't think he'd have a bet. He had - they used to bet in those days but you had to 
have a bit of money I mean it'd only - it'd only be a copper or two if you had a bet. Though there was no greyhound racing if that's what you mean in those days. No greyhound racing, no, greyhound racing was a sport that come later on in years. Long time 
later greyhound racing was. Was only horse racing. And the nearest horse racing was at Alexander Palace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your father or mother belong to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, used - no, what you used to do in those days, you belonged to a slate club. And 
you used to pay all the year round - used to be a - sickness, you know, for sickness. Slate club, used to be slate clubs. And used to be money clubs in those days, be money 'cos they used to call 'em - farthing clubs, used to pay a farthing, double up eve
ry week. From a farthing, ha'penny. Ha'penny penny. Penny tuppence. Tuppence four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11089250\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
pence. Double up to the end of the week. Farthing club. And - but the most popular one was the slate clubs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Who would organise this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, any organisation, the bi
ggest one in that - in - that I can remember was the - the - again it was a - it was to do with the church, it was - what they call - Pleasant Sunday Afternoons. P.S.A. - in Tottenham every - used to have Pleasant Sunday Afternoons, it was a - a semi-reli
g
ious thing, you didn't have to be - go to church. But it was a Pleasant Sunday Afternoon, they - they used to - any school hall, they used to hire some school hall, you was together. The biggest slate club in my area was the PSA. Well I used to belong to 
o
ne at the mission there, we used to call - the - London City Mission slate club. You paid so much a week, case you was ill, and then you used to have a share out at Christmastime. That's where you got your - Christmas money. You had a share out, a few shi
llings and share out, you see, and that - and that bought the Christmas fare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about clothing clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Clothing club, there was clothing clubs. A tallyman was in his - was in his - was in his glory in those days, the tallyman. Always see the tal
lyman. And - clothing - there was clothing clubs. Used to pay so much a week. And you used to - draw - I remember my mother belonging to one and - it was - you draw - you was the first one out, perhaps you'd get about - twenty of you, twenty-four of you, 
p
ay a - so much a week, and you draw for who - who's turn it was to have a share out you see, if you was number one you - you was unlucky, got your clothes and you - it was wore out before you finished paying for it. But - if you was the middle - you draw 
it in the middle of the - say there was about twenty or thirty people and you draw number fifteen you was - all right. Used to draw - there used to be clubs like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would these be organized by neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Always by some - some individual alway
s - always thinking of those schemes. That was the only way you could get anything by clubs. Then there was - of course there was the old pawn shop, that come into its own, the old pawn shop. They wanted any money used to pop it in the pawn shop. The only
 
thing was you'd got to get it out. And I'll tell you what was a racket in those days. Well they had to stop it. And that was carpenters who used to pawn their tools and couldn't get 'em out. And not only that, it - it - it led to being - to - men - people
 
pinching carpenters tools. Pawning 'em. So they had to - had to - pass - I don't know whether there was a law passed by Parliament or what but - it was generally accepted that no pawnbroker would take any tools. He wouldn't take any, he wouldn't know - th
at was a racket in those days, pawn a - if you wanted - and then of course, when they was never - when they was never - redeemed - used to put 'em in the shop window and - flog 'em for a - half the price.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well neighbours, all used to organize - we used to organize }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11811709\charrsid11078316 
our own play. We used to have ta}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
bby cats. There was another game used to have, a game of - used to call - break the alligators back. That was a - that was a kind of a glorified leap frog. Used to - you u
sed to go around in gangs and you used to change your next door - next road to you, who - who was the strongest, you used to have about - four of you would all - the first one was - up against the wall or ups against the fence and - then you would - from 
t
ail - from head to tail you would go along until you eventually had four of you, you see, and then you had to break that - you - the other gang used to have to break that back of that - and, of course the bigger the bloke - the quicker the break was you s
ee. So we used to go about and then who was the - whoever was the - broke the most - alligators backs were the - was the - conquerors you see. They were the - glorified - club they were, gang. Used to go about in gangs in those days. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where did you play as a rule?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
In the street. All in the street, there was no parks about much in those days. There was a park, there was Bruce Castle Park we used to go into, there was Finsbury Park, Bruce Castle Park, but the majority of play - playgrounds - 'c
os it was - in those days as I say the safe - the fastest thing on the roads in those days was the bikes, so there was no motor cars rushing about. The only thing here was horse and carts. Well they was no problem were they when kids were - the only thing
 is when you was playing tibby cat there's more windows broken than - used to have to scoot when you broke somebody's window. Scoot because they used to come out and - they - if you couldn't run fast enough then you was caught you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were you allowed to have children in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, used to have children in the house, used to - have children in the house playing - children in the house, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well yes, you had to get dirty because
 the roads were dirty for a start off, there was no - we used - they used to in summertime they - they used to have the old water cart go round to - lay the dust in the summertime. Water carts used to go round the streets laying the dust. The old - Urban 
C
ouncil used to - lay on a water cart if it got very dry. Water the roads, and use kids used to take our boots and socks off, follow the old water cart round, and we used to get a good hiding for being soaking wet when we got home. Our mothers knew - what 
we'd done, we used to follow the old water cart round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Weren't the roads surfaced properly then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, only just - any old thing used to go on the road in those days. In High Road - Tottenham was all cobblestones. Then they had tar blocks, that pro
ved a - that proved a - a - a very bad that proved 'cos when it - when it got - if it got raining it was flooded all the - tar blocks used to come up. They used to have to lay the tar blocks down in High Road Tottenham. Besides you've got remember that - 
too that - on the main roads there was always trams running. Horse trams. Always tram wheels - tramlines in the road, always tramlines. Always tramlines in the road - in the mainly any main road was always tramlines in it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes. But, I'll tell you what, there was - even in those days there was class distinction. You wasn't allowed to - I can remember people used to say - oh I can't play with you, you're going - you go to chapel while we g
o to church. That's a fact that is. There was that difference between the church and the chapel. We can't play with you, my mum won't let me play with you, you go to chapel. That's a fact.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your mother never discourage you from playing with scruffier children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well, yes, she used to say, be careful, they - they swear too much. Don't play with them if you can avoid it. There was no - there was no - well of course, it's no class distinction so much then in that - you was - you either - you was e
ither poor or you was rich. Or well - put it that way, say rich, you was either poor or you was well off. There was areas like that in Tottenham there was areas where the - where the well off people were. Bruce Grove and all round there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were there any youth organizations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Y.M.C.A. was always there. Y.M.C.A. was always - always - as much - as long as I can remember there was always a Y.M.C.A. and a Y.M.C.A.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you belong to any youth organizations as a boy at school still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, no, n
o. No, there was no youth organization for boys. The schools might - may have an old boys association, like Page boys old boys - Page Green old boys used to have a - an organization. But it'd have to be a big school. A big school like Page Green Road.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have any hobbies as a schoolboy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well used to do fretwork, it used to be fretwork. Yes, the fretwork was very popular in those days amongst boys, fretwork. And so did needlework used to be you know, the - old Singer sewing machines, used to 
be the old handle one. Used to be for the girls used to be sewing. Fretwork used to be, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you keep any pets or do any gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 I say I used to keep pets, rabbits. And - my - we never had - if you wanted chickens you had to have a gar
den, proper good garden for chickens, it's no good having a - a - a concrete - backyard for chickens, that was no good, you could keep rabbits in a concrete backyard, you couldn't keep chickens in a concrete backyard could you. So it's all according what 
g
arden you lived in. You had the back of your house to keep chickens. Chickens were well - chickens were popular - pet. They used to be, chickens because it was a source of food and all you see, fatten your chicken up for Christmas. So you could fatten you
r rabbit up for Christmas. But rabbits were more popular.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you used to go out walking or fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Walking and fishing, yes, you go out fishing. Many a time I've been down the River Lee fishing and the old - used to fish near the locks, because if you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 fe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
ll in the old boatman - the old lock keeper used to hook you up with his - big hook - hook. And many a girl - many a girl's fallen in and he's - hooked 'em out, oh yes, been down the Lee - fall in the Lee, that was - that was a noted - if you ha
dn't fallen in the Lee you hadn't done nothing. Had to fall in the Lee, and the old boat man used to hook you out down the Lee. Tottenham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you used to go swimming as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Swimming, yes, I used to go swimming, yes. Used to go swimming. We u
sed to go swimming in - in your birthday suit in those days, oh yes, never - never - boys never used to - worry about - trunks, you used to go swimming in your birthday suit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Up to about what age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Up to what - about fourteen, I've seen 'em over 
- Hendon - what they call it - Harp - Welsh Harp at Hendon, you know Hendon, Welsh Harp at Hendon, you've heard of the Welsh Ha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 p, they was - right up to about fourteen used to swim in their birthday suits over there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 People not take any notice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, take no notice, no, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 down the River Lee, round Ferrin}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  Lane on the River Lee used to - on the back waters of the ferry used to be - paddling and swimming in the back waters of the Perry in their - in their birthday suits. Used to - Sunday morning used t
o go swimming properly at Sunday mornings my father used to take them all down there. Used to go in the - why they went down to - Park Lane because there was a swimming - club down at Park Lane which - which was an organized - hut with a landing stage. Yo
u
 see, we - they never said nothing to us, I don't know - whether we got permission, I wouldn't know. But any case - we - once we got in the water they couldn't very well say nothing to you so we used to use the - the diving board of the Park Lane swimming
 
pool to - to - to jump - swim in the Lee. 'Cos the - the Lee could be a bit dicey in those days, it could be a - have a - a step, there used to be perhaps about three foot - of - before - you couldn't see nothing but underneath, hidden underneath was abou
t
 three foot of earth you see and if you dived - off the bank, which I've seen many a child dive off the bank, and hit his side on a - or on the protruding - earth that was underneath, hidden underneath the water. So you went on this bank - on this diving 
board - if you was - if you was a good swimmer, if you wanted to swim from lock to lock, you used the - you used the Park Lane swimming - diving board and dived off the side of the board.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So in those days they didn't bother about nudity quite as much as they do now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, I mean to say, no, no. No, used to swim in the - kids - I don't say men. I'm talking about young kids, they never used to worry about birthday - they never had - never had - never had a swimming suit in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you go bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Cycling? I say there used to be - there used to be - racing bicycles, you used to buy them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you have one as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, you - you had - what you used to have, a bicycle in those days if you wanted to go in for bike - racing
 - bicycling - cycling in those days, cycling they used to call it, cycling in those days in a proper manner, you had a - special - bike. It was a - racing frame and the wheels were made of bamboo - wheels. Bamboo, not iron wheels. And your tyres were all
 
in - one. Your inner tube and your outer cover was all in one so if you got a puncture you could - whip it off quick and put another type on you see. And your bamboo was - the bamboo wheels were for lightness. And was always fixed wheel. No free wheels, a
lways fixed wheel. With your - toes in a - bicycle -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where did you used to go cycling as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh used to go anywhere, out Chingford or anything like that. Right out - used to go right out in the country in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 About how old were you when you got your first bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well I suppose the first - we used to hire them in those days, never bought one, you hired. Used to - there used to be a shop you could buy - you could hire your bicycles. So much an hour. Yes, hire a bike. And you 
used to go to - all round to Ware and - Hertfordshire and all round there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were there any other sports you took part in as a schoolboy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well there's football and bicycle, that's all I took part in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about theatres or concerts?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 The
atres, no, you never went - the theatres - there used to be - the Tottenham Palace used to be a music hall, used to go to music halls yes. Used to go as a boy, the music halls, you go up in the gods. What they call the gods. That was the concrete seats up
 there, used to - you used to take - oranges with you because - the orange peel used to come in handy if you didn't like the artistes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents used to go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, no, used to go up just alone. Go on your own. All the kids went on ou
r own, we didn't want our mothers and father with us. We found our own sport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, you - well, used - you used to earn your own pocket money. They never give you any money, they hadn't got no money to g
ive you pocket money, used to earn it. We used to earn it. The - the - the more - the more adaptable you was to earning a - a living the better you - more money you earned you had for yourself. You used to give your mother so much but she used to let you 
k
eep so much, we used to keep - she knew full well you - you used to go - anything you used to do for a copper. Run errands, clean knives. Anything for an errand, your sisters used to clean - girls used to clean doorsteps. Clean somebody's knocker for a pe
nny, ha'penny. All round the brass knockers. Buff it - I tell you what we used to live - get a good living at and that was - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 pl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
ful of horse manure. Yes, we used to knock at the door with the horse manure all fresh today ma'am sort of thing, yes. Well I re
member going - I remember going to one - one boy said, what are you going to do with - one of the - you know, what are you going to do with that? Oh we're going to sell it. What's it good for? Oh, it's good for rhubarb. Oh, he said, we have custard on our
s.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Who would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Neighbours. Neighbours. Neighbours. You was never short of help - if you had good neighbours, you're never short of help in those days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 In what sort of ways did your mother get help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well you'd come and do your washing for you if you was ill. Do your washing for you, the old - no washing machines in those days or no - launderettes in those days, you d
id the old zinc bath and scrubbing brush, they used to do your washing for you. Yes, women used to do the washing. Come in and do your washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How many relatives did you have living nearby?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well we never had many relatives living by there, the
re - my - my aunt - was - one was at Whittisham, one was at Kettering. All far away. That was - they was - that was - that was our sources of holidays if - for our aunt live in the country. Source of holiday for you if you had aunt in the country, you - y
ou was well off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How much did you see of your relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh quite a lot. Oh yes, yes. Oh yes. There was one at Walthamstow used to come over, my aunt - cousin Any used to come over quite a lot, see her Uncle - Uncle Harry. She was - she was a sch
oolteacher and she - I say to - to us she was comfortable - she had a good - steady income you see, schoolteachers were paid - I don't know whether they was paid well or what I couldn't tell you but they used to be a source of - it was at regular income, 
there was no question of short time or wet time or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 There were the relatives your father worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Relatives - oh yes, me - me father worked with, they used to come, used to visit. They used to come down very often, Uncle Fred.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents have many friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, had a lot of friends, my mother did, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where would they see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 All round, all - all in the area where she lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where would they meet them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 In the house, meet in the
 house. They used to come in the house. Used to have a cup of char in those days in the house. Teapot used to be on the - teapot was always - was always on the go, the teapot in those days. Teapot - and the coffeepot. Always had a coffee pot and a teapot.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your father's friends come round the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, they'd come round the house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would you say the people that came round were mainly your mother's friends or your father's friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well a bit of each I think, me mother's friends, me father's friends and neighbours you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your mother and father have a different set of friends or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, they were - it was a - the - the wife of the - me father - the wife of me father's friend would be - my mother's friend you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How often would friends come round in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh any time, they come in any time of day in those days. Just drop in casually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 They would be offered a drink, there was always a coffee pot and a teapot made, that was always being made, coffee pot and teapot.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents go out visiting friends or relations much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, they went out visiting friends, yes. Not far away, was - you - you see - there wasn't the travel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 in
g facilities in those days. All there was was a - old horse and - horse cars and - then they - they did in the finish got electric cars - electric trams but - I remember the old horse trams and the horse buses. Oh yes, I remember the old horse buses and h
orse trams, then it got - then they got the electric trams. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 People used to make their own amusements then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What did your parents used to do when their friends came round or when they visited friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well you had to
 go into the other room when they - had to make yourself scarce. Well you'd have books to read and - magazines to read, there was always books to read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What would the grown ups do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 The grown ups would be - they would play some sort of dominoes o
r - or - draughts and things like that. Cards perhaps if you was a card player. I remember my mother teaching me how to play - oh what was it - oh - there was one card my mother was very fond of. Not - you had a - a board with - crib, oh yes, she was very
 fond, she taught me how to play crib. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Many people divide society into different social classes, at that time before 1918 what would you say the different social classes were?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well it was very - it was very very pronounces wasn't it, very pronounced. Yes, very pronounced.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What would you say they were?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
I should say - what we call the affluent society was the middle class - there used to be - the - the middle class used - then that used to be divided into two, there's the upper m
iddle class and the lower middle class. All round Stamford Hill - used to have their servants, used to have their - if you - if you was a little bit - affluent you had a - nursemaid, and a - kitchen - and a kitchen maid. Always had a nursemaid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How about below the middle class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well, they used to - I - I don't know what happened to them, I - I - all I remember was - the two classes that - how they would live I wouldn't know after that but - if you - was - even as - if you was - what shall I - how
 shall I put it, if you had - if you wanted to be somebody you had to have a nursemaid. OR A Housemaid. That's where the girls from the country used to come and - if - country girls used to come as the housemaids and nursemaids. Most of the country girls,
 
and the country - and the chaps from the country used to be policemen. Great big burly chaps. There was a - there was policeman in - now - in - in nearly every road. Policeman used to have his beat, night time and daytime, always a police beat, always out
, you see 'em all - from Tottenham police station you always see 'em line up and they'd all walk out with their - great line of 'em used to walk out and go to their different beats.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What sort of class would you put policemen in in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Wel
l - they was - the - working class but they was the - elite of the working class because they had a regular - look - if you had a regular job, like a postman - a fireman or a policeman then you was - then you was really - somebody in the working class mov
ement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What would you split the working class into then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well I should put working class into labourers, artisans and - schoolteachers. Semi-professional.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You'd put schoolteachers as working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well yes, used to have - because they
 come in contact - and they used to do a good job of work with the poorer class, the schoolteachers. Used to do a good job of work for the kiddies because they used to see the - the - the - what shall I call it, the - inequality of it because they used to
 come - some kidd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
es used to come to work without any breakfast. And they used to see it. And some of those schoolteachers used to give 'em a meal. Especially when there was a break playtime, they used to; make tea for 'em and give 'em - little bits and pie
ces out of their own - out of their own pocket. Schoolteachers, I know several of the schoolteachers used to give those poorer classes the - the what do you call it, the - underprivileged class, there was a lot of underprivileged children in those days, a
 
lot of underprivileged children. Go to school in - I remember there used to be a boot fund. One of the M.P.'s for the - for Hornsey, he had a boot fund. And he - he - all most of the children used to come - in some - in summertime used to come to work - s
chool in plimso}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 ls. And of course only rubber, and used to be hole in the middle of them.
