i
t's not - it doesn't happen now but in those days as I think I told you the - my daughter - my sister said - she had a friend and - suddenly her friend dropped her. So we made enquiries and they - she - her friend said to my sister, oh well my mum says, m
u
stn't make too much of a friend of you, you're chapel. You see, well that's the sort of attitude. There was a bit of a - class distinction I reckon, you see. 'Cos you were all - there was all the - the top hated and the bowler hated people went to church.
 I won't say that's - there was quite a lot of people in the church who were interested in the movement. But - I fancy th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 ey patronized the working class}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
