\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No, no, I mean to say my mother and father didn't - never - never had - any - what shall I say - antagonism to anybody, she was placid sort of - don't matter who you were. But mind you, she - she - used to - be very timid if some
body was a little bit affluent. She would approach them with a sort of - she - she knew she was poor and - and she used to approach 'em with a kind of a timid - approach you see. But - I say anybody with money in those days, real money - was never - they 
w
ere gentlemen, gentlemen and ladies, they always approached the - the poorer class with dignity. They never looked down on 'em, never talked down on 'em. Understand my - only the - people who - wanted to be - you know, their own authority, they was - self
 
appointed - judges and self appointed bosses, they only - they was the people who - who started being a bit - catty or something like that you know, and stand-offish or snooty. But we never used to worry about them, we used to turn our noses up, we never 
used to worry about them, we got on without it, we never used to worry about those people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, all she - all she cared about - was she - was she regards as a clean an
d a honest living woman. That's all she troubled about, never about her - her station in life, it never worried her, her station in life. As long as-she was respected for her - integrity, that's all my - and that's all my father cared about. If he was res
pected for his integrity that's all he wanted to worry about you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you think it was possible in those days to move from one class to another or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, not so very well, you had to be very well educated to do it and - education was not a -
 well we - there was a - distinction demark - line of demar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
ation between the - elementary schoolboy and the - well there was grammar schools in those days and the public school but there was a definite - cleavage between the two distinct - and it was - ma
rked in every respect. Marked in every - there was the first class railway was - was always - I suppose that's where the railway started the first class - distinction, there was a first and second and third class. We betide if a working man found his way 
in, even into the second class. The ticket inspector used to come round and - cor luv a duck, you - go on, back you go, third class. It - that used to happen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh there was always policemen round, everybody - every street had a policeman, even at night times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What did you think of him - when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What did we - when you was a boy you was frightened of him. He ruled the - he ruled the street, I mean to say - I'v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 e been - they used to push you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316 f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 f the pavement and they used - if you was in groups of three or four, they would push you on, they would - you couldn't gather at the corners, street corners, oh no. You was not allowed to gather in street corners in grou
ps. You would have to keep on the move. They would come up and push you on the move. There was policemen on either side of the road in those days, yes.
