\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How do you think they treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What, the policemen? Well he had - some - like they ar
e today, some people had their - likes and dislikes. I know - and when - I lived in Chestnut Road there was a - a family there, this chap - this man liked his pint, he used to go up the Eagle, he liked his pint, he used to have a pint. And he'd come home 
o
f a night time and there was a policeman on the beat down there - used to wait for him to do something wrong, you know, like - fall over. And he never got - at last he caught him. Do you know he done. Triped him up as he went into the gate. He was - he wa
s
 known as that - P.C.39 I think they used to call him, and he was a - he was the - arch enemy of the - of the - of the people in that locality. He - he - he - he tripped him up as he - he got absolutely frustrated I think, he couldn't - couldn't - you kno
w
, he know - he knew - this policeman knew he'd had a skinful but he was able to carry it. And he was so anxious to catch him - that when he got to his gate and he - he - he tripped him and he fell over and that was what he liked, he found him in the stree
t see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How did they treat the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Boys? Oh well - you - you - I remember - I remember one Christmas time we was looking in a - the Post Office up the top of our road and it had Christmas goods in it. And we was looking in there, both - us - my 
friend and I was looking in there most intently and all of a sudden,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8024667\charrsid11078316  oh we had a clip round the ear h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
ole, it was a cold night - and the lobes of your ear was frozen, and this copper had a knick - knack of - or most coppers did in those days, had a knack of
 flicking their gloves - onto the lobe of your ear, how they did it I don't know, it used to be - I very nearly cried of pain. And of course you had - you moved on. And if they didn't do that they used - they used their cape as a - as a - as a - you know 
u
sed to clout you with the cape. Oh yes, you didn't - no come nicely with policemen in those days. They ruled. No good you - ah there were some policemen who - who - who - in some areas where they was - what shall I say - real - gangs - as I say, real - tr
o
uble you see but they - they seemed to - rule - they seemed to rule 'em you see and - had a knack of ruling 'em. They say, now next time you do it, I'll clout you own and all that sort of thing and the - and the young boy knew that he was going to get a g
o
od hiding from the copper instead - of him - pinching him and going up to court and everything. He used to - he used to - he used to - self administer punishment. And some of the policemen used to get - used to get respect by that. If they - self administ
ered punishment in those days, they didn't worry about - they knew devils, they knew boys were devils in those days. There was another one would live with - another - another class of people - copper would - delight in - hauling you in.
