er had - never - nobody had holidays with pay, no firm had holidays with pay until after the first world - second world war. I got a job at at the Co-op, before the first world war - second world war - I - I come out on strike at Levis' so I - had to - go
 
all over the place. I went - I was - I don't come in your group now 'cos I - I'm a married man, but - nobody got paid for holidays in those days. Except the apprentices. OH I'll tell you something, when I - were going down to work at Levis' - Lord Haldane
, you talk about holidays with pay, that did come}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
in, that did come in. Lord Haldane fetched out the Territorial Army - Bill, and he approached all firms with any - sizeable employer - young men who - sizeable size - numbers - to encourage them to join the 
Territorial Army, and would they grant a fortnight's leave for camp in the summer time. And would they augment - now you got paid regular Army pay when you went to this camp from the Army, would they augment your - pay by say half pay - if you was earning
 
- if you was work - working. Would they encourage you to join? And grant you a fortnight's leave without any question. Well that was immediately was - well was a - an incentive for boys to - for young boys to - join up, you see, join the Territorial Army,
 
was a source of pay, a fortnight's holiday per - on a - at Salisbury Plain or some other place you see. And you got paid for it. The firm - Levis' did, they - they give you permission. And - we - you - you got - you - you went to your - exercise every for
tnight - every year, fortnight's holiday, well I was only in it two year before the war broke out so - I only went to two camps.
