 Saturdays. One o'clock Saturdays every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 And you didn't have holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
There was no every holidays no. No. Sunday the only day off and your half a day Saturday. Half a day, well then that - there was only - when you - in the evening
 there was only blooming candlelight and - paraffin lamps to - then later on you had gas put in, so - and they was only a flicker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you feel that your wage was a fair one at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well I - never thought about it. I never - well they went 
right on until the first world war started. It wasn't 'til the - it wasn't until the first world war started that people began to take notice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you still give the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, I was married - I - I got married in 1917 you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 But up until 1917?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, well - up 'til I joined the Army used to give my mother her money, that was our board and keep you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would she give you so much back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, she used to say, I want so much money for keep. Well if you had a pound well he'd want say fifteen bob for keep.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How did you get on with the people you worked with there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 All right. You - yes, all right. Used to have your larks. Likes and dislikes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What about the employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - they was a bit
 of martinets you see, you daren't - you daren't idle your time away and if they thought - saw you laughing they was wondering what sort of game you was up to you see so you - you had to be - you had to be - you had to be a - a busy busy. Busy bee in thos
e days. Appear to be a busy bee at any rate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - it was a job. When I was apprenticed I was - no fear of being out of work. It was secure. What you - everything that was secure you went for, if it was - if it was secure, don't matter if the wages were low so long as it was secure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Do you think starting full time work when you first started changed your attitude to school in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No. No. You - you used to look forward to leaving school in any case.
 Although you knew you'd got to go out to work you used to look forward to leaving school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What jobs have you done since the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Still in the trade, I was in me - in the trade you see, so I'd learnt - I'd finished me apprenticeship,
 so I was able to go into a trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 When did you retire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well when I was - I - I worked 'til I was seventy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would you have preferred a different type of occupation or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Had no choice, you - you couldn't go and get a - you couldn't c
hange - you couldn't - you couldn't change your - occupation with - just like that in - after you'd - trained - after you'd been working say for - twenty or thirty years, you couldn't just change your occupation - with any sort of competence because you -
 you - you hadn't been trained for anything else, only your job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you belong to the trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes, I was - I played an active part in my trade union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What sort of part did you play?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well I used to go - used to go and be on th
e - yes, it comes later, yes. But if you want to know I'll tell you. I was - elected to - on the District Management Committee and used to meet once a month to discuss the - the work - the - the workings of the union you see, the - all the accidents and a
ll that sort of thing come before the District - District Management Committee, and you'd - you was amalgamated to the - see, I was a woodcutter machin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 st. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Which union was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Woodcutting Machinists. Wood - it was called - but the - the A
malgamated Society of Woodcutting Machinists was affiliated to a trade. The cabinet trade, the building trade and the pianoforte trade, the saw}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 milling trade. That union - my union was affiliated to about four different trades. They're all - they were diff
erent industries and they all had their own particular - agreements. So - you had to know - if you was - I was elected on the building - on the furnishing trade, NAFTA, so I knew all about the workings of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 the NAFTA. And - but my - as a r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 epresentative of th
e Amalgamated Society of Woodcutting Machinists, I was the - I was on the build - on the furnishing trade side of it. My mater if he was in the building trade he could be - a woodcutting machinist affiliated to the building trade you see. It would be a di
f
ferent - he would view the agreement on a different angle to what I viewed it in. See, it's all according how - strong you was, you got - different agreements. For instance - we - we had a forty-seven hour week, we gained a forty-seven hour week in a five
 
- in a five day week, for five - forty-seven hours in a five day week. The building trade stuck to their forty-four hour - week and an eight hour day. That was their - I don't say all - there was overtime to be worked but - the principle - the basic - the
 
basic rule was forty-four hours, eight hours a day and that was four hours Sunday - Saturday. Well whenever - after - when we - we reached an agreement - we never worked Saturday because we did our forty-seven hours in a five day week, so we never worked 
o
n a Saturday. There was still - that was still trade union - it was still - we wasn't - blacklegging anybody or wasn't - it wasn't - doing anything wrong. It was the agreement. So the different trades - different - sections of the industry - different ind
ustries had their different agreements. Although you belonged to one union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 In the early days did you feel that employers and workers had the same interests or different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well you - you looked upon your employer as an enemy. That was - that was -
 that was how you had to - visualize it, your employer was - was - he was out to get as much out of you - as he possible could for as least - as little money as he possibly could pay. That was the attitude, that's how you had to look at it, there was no o
t
her way to look at it. It was the survival of the fittest, your guv'nor the boss. He wanted you to work forty-seven hours for a shilling an hour. You didn't want to work forty-seven hours for two bob an hour or something like that. So - you pitted your - 
intelligence and weight against him. The only resource you got was a strike.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Some people say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh there was, that was - that was a sore point. That was a so
re point. Because - if you went in the building trade, the carpenter, the real carpenter, he was the joiner, the real joiner, he was the - he was the elite of the - of the woodworkers, he was the joiner. There were the carpenters, joiners and like anythin
g
 else one was a little bit more superior. A joiner was looked - classes - as the elite, he was the - finishing touch to the woodworking - the joiner - the building trade in the wood line. He would have what they call a hard hat. That's a - that's a poor m
a
n's top hat, if you know what a hard hat is. It's a poor man's top hat. And he would never start a job unless there was a box to put his top hat in. And if he hadn't one he used to make one, that was the accepted - carvers. Carvers, they were the elite, t
h
ey were the elite of the lot mate. They used to have - covers - cuffs, loose cuffs in - used to have a shirt and then have a - a loose cuff, you know, used - then take - take the loose cuff off, and perhaps have a trilby hat or bowler hat. They would go i
n - they would go in. Then there was the office staff, they always - they never - never started until the - 'til nine o'clock and you used to come in at half past seven, that was the distinction between the office staf}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 f and the - with the white colla}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 r workers, that was the difference. There was always that - there was always that bar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
ier. Always that - not so much now, being all workers now, it's different, but in those days - the barrier was there. And then there was the labourer, he - well he was the lowes
t that he could - I wouldn't say the lowest, that's the wrong word to use, he was the - well I suppose it - nothing else to used it for that. You understand, not in a - not in a ridiculous - not in - not ridicule. Those labourers in those days used to be 
o
ut - labourers used to be outside the factory, I remember I worked for - Jaegers, he was a proper old Jew boy he was, and he used to - he said to the labourers - said to one lot of labourers there he says, you're only going to get a shilling an hour. See?
 
One bloke said to him, well, he said - I shan't be able to buy no meat and nothing for Sunday joint, he said. He said, I'll only have to buy fish. Live on fish all the time, a shilling an hour, I shan't be able to get any meat. He said, well - fish makes 
brain, he said, we don't brains to make - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 won't shift this bloody great b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
arrel will, you want brawn. You see. Well if he didn't like it he had - he could - there was half a dozen blokes outside the gate waiting to come in. He - he - he - the guv'nor didn't 
worry. He knew full well if that bloke didn't want to work - work for a shilling an hour he'd got somebody outside who would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What sort of ways do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - my - my job changed my life to the fact that I had to - use my - know how in my trade to get a living. The more I knew - to my job, the more money I could get. So. So I was not going to - go and work for any Tom, Dick and Harry at any - 
any old price. So I valued my - brains and my - skill. I valued my skill at a certain sum of money and that was what I was going to get. And I was determined to get it. And I got it. You had to have confidence in - you had to have confidence in your abili
t
y. For instance there was a - I went to work for one place and - and he had - the - the boss had a moan to me, he said I wasn't fast enough, so - one of the shop stewards come up to me, and he said, if you get the sack for being slow that's no disgrace. H
e
 said, you can walk out. But if you get the sack for bad work then you've got to - sit up and take notice. Don't be worried about getting the sack because you're slow. You've got to worry about getting the sack for bad work, and that was a - that is perfe
c
tly true, if you was a good workman, did your job and it took you half an hour to do it but it was a good job after you'd done it then you had no worry had you. But that didn't always - that didn't always go down with firms, they wanted it quick, sharp an
d handy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you continue to live at home until you joined the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh, the only place you could live isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh no, no, you still come home and fetched your wages to your mother, you wasn't half - you wasn't half proud too and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you spend your Sunday any differently after you started working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No, well - you had a - you be - you became engaged in different activities didn't you, you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 re - 
when you started work, you joined different clubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you tell us about these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well - we started taking an interest in football, so I joined the football club. Every Saturday afternoon used to play football. At your own expense. And you used 
to be delighted in the winter time, in the summer time - we used to go cycling. I bought a cycle out of - eighteen - eighteen pence a week. Used to go cycling with - with a - your mates. Chingford, all round there. But always went to church on Sundays, I 
did. Yes, still - still carried on the - church work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you start to take an interest in politics at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes I did, after - I did - I did start - when I come out the Army I did, not before. Not before, you didn't take much notice of poli
tics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you vote at all in 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well you - you - well you didn't vote - you voted in - I voted - I wasn't entitled to vote was I until you become twenty-one - in any case.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You'd be twenty-one in 1918 wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Yes, well then a
 few years - soon after that I was in the Army wasn't I, so I would - I wouldn't - I was in the Army soon - I think about two years after I was twenty-one I was in the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 But did you vote in the election in 1918? 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 1919 I was out - I was 
out of the Army then wasn't I. And I did then, I used - I joined the Labour party. I joined the Labour party after I come out the first world war, a load of us joined the Labour party because - 'cos we realized the - the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You think that was as a result of your experiences in the wars,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Yes, in the war, yes, that attitude. You see, Lloyd George said he was going to have homes fit for heroes to live in. Well when we come home we were sadly - disillusioned. Loads of people joined the Labour party af
ter the first world war because - they realized it was such a - a difference between the - haves and the have nots - they decided to alter the situation if we could. And we decided that it should - we should - this war should be the - the - end of - no mo
re war, but it didn't work out that way did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you take an active part in the party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 I took an active part, used to go round canvassing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you go out at all in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well we used - there was not much to go to I mean to s
ay - unless you went to a music hall. Cinemas, it was all - you went to the cinemas but you got fed up with all silent pictures weren't there then those days. There were some pictures you went to but - even in those days it was - money that - kept you fro
m going too far.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you make any new friends at this time before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
1918? Well I made a lot of friends you see didn't I, I - I started courting. Before 1918, I started courting in 19 - 1914 - 1914 I started courting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you used to take your friends home at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh used to take your friends, oh yes. Used to gather round, used to have games in - in hour own home, used to have games, yes. All sorts of games used to have - in your own home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents expect to know where you were when you were out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh they wanted to know where you were, yes, even then - even in those days they wanted to know and - the girl, she couldn't come home - she couldn't come home late after ten o'clock at night even although she was cou
rting. See, they was very strict. I remember my grandmother telling me that she got a slap - although she was courting and getting married the next week she got a slap round the face because she was late home. Her father said, this is - Sarah, you're late
.
 She said, well I - I'm - I'm all right, she said, I though - he said, don't argue with me, and he slapped her round the face, and she never - never forgive her father for it. That was the attitude in those days. Girls. They wanted to know where their gir
ls were, but I mean that didn't stop them from getting into trouble just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where would you go when you were courting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well - round the churchyard. Or up in some dark place they go now - like they go now. Where you wasn't seen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you carry on still with your football on Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh yes, Saturday, that was all, and she used - I used to have - I used to have a - a follower then, my girlfriends used to come and - come and watch us, all - all - all the chaps used to have their gi
rlfriends used to watch 'em playing football and they used to shout for you. I joined the band. I joined the band. And we used to go out, in - in - in the wintertime we used to go out - what they call - waites, with waites, you know, waite they spell it, 
a
nd you used to - used to meet at half past eleven at night, and used to - the band used to split up into groups of three or four, there was always a cornet player amongst them or - or a tenor player, who could take the lead part. And you - then you had so
m
ebody who could do the om-pa, oom-pa part of it to make it sound a bit - solid. Either the trombone or the base player or the euphonium player, used to gather round the lamp posts and we used to say three times round the lamp post. About half past - eleve
n
 at night, this was when I was - when I was young, before 1914. Used to gather round the lamp post at night and play this - and - oh by the way, somebody used to say to you, when you come in our street play outside my house will you? Then you can all come
 
in - for a mince pie and a cup of coffee. Cor that was - champion that was. Well - we'd stand outside the lamp post, or this particular person's house - they would request you to play the Mistletoe Bough, or - While Shepherds watched their flocks one nigh
t
, any favourite carol you had to play. And you play by it ear, the - the lamp post was only a blinking old - flicker of a gas lamp, that's all it was but - you - you played it so often that you - if you made a false note nobody ever knew but it was - nobo
d
y was watching you or listening to you. But you could hear these - now it was really - a really - good sight. Or - what shall I say, an inspiration, 'cos you'd hear - Stamford Hill you could hear - the - the night was silent. There was no noise, no traffi
c
. And you would hear half a dozen bands in the - in the area playing these - playing these Christmas carols. And you could lay in bed - and I remember laying in bed sometimes, and these - these - these bands used to come round playing these carols. And it
 used to be a - it used to be a peaceful sight. Peaceful. The Salvation Army - every Salvation Army had a band. If you were the Salvation Army's Citadel, any - of any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 calibre}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 , it had a band. I don't say it was all good bandsman, but they used to have a band
, they used to make a noise. That's all what you wanted weren't it? There was the working - there was - there - in my area I suppose where I lived there must have been - four bands.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 What did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 I used to play a soprano cornet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 You said you joined the Territorials?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 I joined the Territorials - two years before the war finished. I joined the Fusiliers, the London Regiment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So you went on camps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Went on camps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Were these like a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 That was a holiday, that was the cheap holiday wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Where did you go with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 Pur}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
bright or anywhere, we used to go all sorts of camps, any - any camp that the regular army had for camping and practicing, military exercises you went to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 And you got married in 1917?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
1917, after I - after I - you see I joined - you had to join for four years. If you joined the Territorials because it - and that was binding. They could pinch you for not - for not - we lived an Army life like a normal Army - regular soldi
er would live, but I mean - carried out the same - the same sort of - training as a regular Army, used to go out and - night - night patrol - you know, night exercises.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How old were you when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh - yes, about twenty-five I suppose. I was about twenty-five I was married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How long had you known your wife then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Well I - I married - I picked her up in - well that's the wrong word to use, picked her up, I fell in love with her, put it that way. Which is quite correct. I - t
his is really - you - you - you talk about love at first sight, this really happened to me. Yes. I - I told you I belonged to a football team. Well - my mate, Fred Arrow well, was getting married. And he was married at - he was getting married to a young 
g
irl that lived at Walthamstow. And he was getting married at St Andrews church in Walthamstow, out at Hiham Hill. So we all decided we'd buy him a present. And we all - we all decided that we'd go - to see him married. Although we hadn't been invited to t
h
e wedding I mean to say you - you - you couldn't afford to - invite any Tom, Dick and Harry in those days, it was a - it was a - it was a bit of an effort to get - get married and have a decent - everybody tried to get married, I mean to say - they always
 
gave their daughters a good white wedding if they could. If it was a white wedding occasion. But then - then - sometimes that didn't always happen like that but still if you got your daughter a white wedding you was very pleased and you'd do it. If it was
 your last penny. So you never invited any Tom, Dic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
, and Harry to come to the wedding, they could come to the wedding and watch - see you married, come to the church and - if you got invited home perhaps that's all the - all the batter, you could always go
 and join in the the - the fun - the fun and frolics afterwards. But you never enjoyed - you never - you never - you never was invited to the wedding breakfast because that was - a bit more expensive, so - so we - we decided we'd go to this - see him marr
ied at this church. And I went to this church and we're all waiting for the bride and bridegroom to come out. And - while we were waiting for the bride and bridegroom to come - come out - we were standing on either side to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 he doorway, right opposite me was
 a young girl. And I kept looking at her and she kept on looking at me. And - I thought, oh that's all right, there's a nice bit of - bit of stuff there so I - she would cotton on see. I suppose she was - same sort of thing was running through her mind. S
o
 when - when Fred Arrowell came out, we was cheering him and throwing - confetti over him and it turned out that my wife was a cousin of his - of the bride. See? She was a cousin of the bride and hadn't - and had been invited to the wedding - breakfast. S
o - and my mate was the bride }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  bride}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316  groom}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
, Fred Arrowell, so he see me there so he said, come on Stan. We'll - you can come home, so - when I come home there was - my wife there at the same time and of course - from that day onwards, that must have been 1
912, from that day onwards we - we - we never missed seeing one another. And she lived at Clannan Road Hornsey and I lived at Tottenham. We used to court - you know what we used to - how we used to - 'cos there's no buses in those days running down - Turn
pike Lane or anything like that, so - we used to have to walk - I used to have to walk from High Cross Road Tottenham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So there were no buses down Turnpike Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 No buses, not down Turnpike Lane to Tottenham in those days, you could go on the old
 electric tram, the old boneshakers as we used to call them, right the way round in the main streets sort of thing. Like from High Road Tottenham, all up Bruce Grove and round again into High Road, Wood Green. That was a roundabout way but the direct way 
w
as right through, there was no buses run, you see. So - I had a bike, as I told you I went in the bike and - and the back of the back, the back wheel we used to have extended nuts, about that - about three or four inches long, you could put on the back - 
a
s another nut you see, fixed to the back wheel - on either side. Well my - I used to - pick my wife up on the bike, she wanted to come my - visit my parents, I used to cycle up to her house, then she used to stand on the - the extended nuts with her - you
 
know, stand on them then put her hand on my shoulder and I used to cycle from - cycle from - Clarendon Road, Hornsey, to West - to - High Cross Road Tottenham with her on the back of my bike and we used to enjoy it too. Oh yes, but of course you could cyc
le in those days with a certain amount of - security, I mean to say.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How long were you engaged for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Oh - up until the war started. We was going to get married when the war broke out, we had to - I had to go and join the Army so - I had to go as 
they - being in the Territorials I was the one that - I was the first one - we were - all the Territorial Army - were the first to be - called - conscripted you see, all the lot was conscripted then. And that - it was a good job it was because it saved - 
t
he - the Territorial Army saved the British Army didn't it, 'cos it - I - I was in France fighting in 19 - 1915. In 1914 I was sent to Malta - our regiment was - the four battalions of the Royal Territorial Fusiliers was sent to Malta, the four battalions
 
of the Royal Fusiliers, first, second, third and fourth was sent to Malta - to relieve the regulars in Malta. Another was sent to Gibraltar to relieve the regulars in - in Gibraltar, so - there was a - a flow of regular Army people, real professional sold
iers going out to France to take the blunt of the attack. Well, when 19 - when - December came we was all - told that we was going home, but - we - started getting a bit - a bit excited but then they found we - we was down - we was do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 wn for Marseill}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 es in France, instead of going home to England we was down for Ma}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 seilles in France - we was in the thick of it in 1915. Thic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16476657\charrsid11078316 k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316  of it, there was a - actually fact the London Scottish were - before that. We was really - we was really in the thick of the - in the bus
iness - was the Territorial Army in those days. At any rate the Fusiliers were. I - I can show you a cutting a I had from a - yes, I'll show you the cutting of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did you save up any money before you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well used to have a bank book. 
I used to save up to get married. Save up when you buy anything. And you used to put about a couple of - oh I'll tell you what we used to do in those days. You could buy savings - you could buy stamps on a form, and when you got a shilling on a form you c
ould put it in your bank book. Now that's what I used to do. Used to have so many - every stamp - you buy so many stamps until you got a - a form filled - of penny stamps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did your parents help you at all in setting up a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, now mean to s
ay - sometimes they would if you - if you - well they never had much of a home for them blooming selves, there was no - no elaborate things or any - in your home in those days you only had the essentials. In - in a lot of cases people only had the essenti
als.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 When did you first set up your first home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
When I - when I come out the Army. I set it up because I had a - I had a certain amount of money coming from - from the Army you see. I lived with my mother-in-law the first - for the - for about two years. And I bought me bits and pieces.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 So that would be about 1920?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
1921 when I first - when I first bought me own home, had a - we had a council house, went - went to Culforth Estate you see on the Hornsey council. And I bought me own home then, furniture and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Could you tell us about your wedding, like how many guests or what sort of presents you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Well, was only - was only - there was only relations, there - you saw that photograph. That was - that was - no, that wa
s the wedding group. That was the number of people who was there at the wedding. They're all relatives, of both parties, that's all who went to weddings, you see, some - the two bridesmaids were my - my nieces.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Who's the gentleman, is that her father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
Where - what - what - her father wasn't there, he - he died. Oh it - yes he was there, yes. Well that commercial traveller was a - was a - was a family friend. He was my brother's father-in-law. There's my sister-in-law. There's my - there's my sist
er, there's my mother. I told you my father wasn't there, he - he wouldn't walk - he wouldn't pay the fare to come to - the pictures on a Sunday it was a Sunday. There's my - there's my mother-in-law. There's my sister-in-law. There's my - these are all -
 all the lot are relations. All the lot relations.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 How old was your wife when you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Three years younger than me so you see she would be about twenty-three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Had she worked before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Oh yes. Housework. She - she used to go out - go out daily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Did she work after marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 
No. No. I say you never - we were never - in after - unless it was daily work - perhaps - she would do daily - I wouldn't let her go out to work. You never let - you never - you never - you nev
er - you tried hard not to send your wife out to work, because - you - if she did go out to work you never told anybody. In any case - it would be housework, she'd have to do - there was nothing else for a woman to do. My sister - it wasn't until my - it 
w
asn't until - just before the first world war - that there was - building factories, for women to go out to work, my sister went to Flatoes, the boot factory you see. They started mass producing boots - they started mass producing - the Eagle pencil compa
n
y stated, they was - mass producing pencils in a - in a large number, that was the Eagle pencil factory. All over - all over Tottenham - and on the marshland at Tottenham they started building factories. There was the Eagle Pencil Company, there was - Mil
l
ingtons. There was Gestetner's, the rotary people, they started there. Oh yes, they started down there. All round there. So there was - there was - gradually women were coming into - work, just before the - just - just before the first world war. You see,
 because - I was at Levis' at the time and I was a young man and - there was - where I lived in High Cross Road and all that there was a load of Jew boys used to - a load of - Jewish - refugees came from - Poland and Russia.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7218946 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 When was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10358713 SB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15817354\charrsid11078316 Just 
before the first world war. And - they congregated round Colsmith Road, High Cross Road - and all round the side turnings round - Tottenham Hale, and they used to - that was really - it was - rumoured that there was about thirty-three in a house. And Levi
s
' absorbed quite a lot of 'em because they was - unskilled workers and there was a lot of unskilled work so Levis - and those factories around there absorbed quite of lot of them. But then - it become so bad - that - there was a really conflict. Somebody 
w
ent into Levis' for a job, two blokes went into Levis' for a job, and couldn't get taken on and they saw these - refugees, put it that way if you like, they wasn't - well I suppose they were emigrants but they wasn't - emigrants in the term we know, they 
-
 they'd fled from Poland and all round there, they were the Jewish - they had a Pogrom didn't they - they come from the ghettos of - Russia and Warsaw and - and all that, they fled over here, they was given asylum over here, they had to go somewhere so th
e
y lived in these places, about three or four - families lived in one house. And it became so - as I say, they came - had to live so they was given the factories used to take 'em in. But Levis' - when that - two chaps went down to Levis' to get a job they 
w
ere - they were sent down - to Levis' and they found that they couldn't get a job so - they wrote on the - the vacancy board outside the factory - no Englishmen need apply. Well of course - the Labour Exchange had just started up and the Labour Exchange w
a
